1315	94b7dcf8-14fe-4855-a4b3-df748daa00fd	People React to Being Told They're Beautiful, Their Reaction Will Make You Cry	people-react-to-being-told-theyre-beautiful-their-reaction-will-make-you-cry	\nIt’s the strangest phenomena to me, and I can admit that I am not outside of it.  I, generally-speaking, do not think that I am a very attractive person.  I boast of confidence and act as though not much bothers me, but that’s only because it’s easier to find happiness once you’ve accepted the reality of your life and start being yourself.\n\nHave you ever told someone that they’re beautiful?  I probably think it to myself at least a handful of times everyday when watching and interacting with the various people in my life, but I rarely ever voice it.  In both men and women I am able to look at them and find something attractive and beautiful about them.\n\nHow could you not?  Every single person on this planet is a unique, beautiful, stunning, miraculous bundle of tissue, nerves and consciousness.  And while I (and I assume many others) am able to see the beauty inherent within every person, I’d venture to guess that most of us don’t view ourselves that way.\n\nAn 18-year-old student from Chicago embarked on a high school project that would quickly become much larger than she had anticipated.  **[Shea Glover](https://www.instagram.com/gloverfull/)** invited students and teachers to pose for portraits; some of whom she knew, some of whom were total strangers.\n\nAs these people were standing in front of her camera, she would tell them the purpose of the project: “I’m taking pictures of things I find beautiful.”\n\nThe following video documented the beautiful, raw emotion that is expressed when people are caught a tiny bit off guard by being told they’re beautiful.  It is truly amazing the power that one word holds.  Watch and remember that you are just as beautiful as the next person, in your own, unique, perfect way.\n\n<iframe allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" height