1325	f44b3103-83d2-4225-8b34-f481652ee918	3 Marriage Mistakes Everyone Makes	3-marriage-mistakes-everyone-makes	\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">For those of us who are in committed relationships or who are striving to find that special someone to call our own, happiness is at the top of the priority list.  The thing is, being in a relationship where you both have intense feelings for one another often causes us to act and think in ways that we normally wouldn’t.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">So, we’re in love and we’re striving to build a lasting happiness with our significant other, but at the same time we’re also acting a bit crazy because of these strong emotions, and this is where problems arise.  And more often than not, these problems arise because one partner is unknowingly doing things that the other partner doesn’t like.  Because if you knew that you were doing something hurtful toward your significant other, you’d stop right?</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Here are three mistakes that everyone makes when they’re deep into a relationship:</span>\n\n**Failing to take ownership of problems – **<span style="font-weight: 400;">Working hard at a relationship often leads us to believe that things are going well, so when problems comes up or when fights occur, we tend to be left scratching our heads as to what happened.  And then we usually shift blame to our partners, because we’re trying hard, so it can’t be us.  Wrong.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Blaming your partner is the easiest thing to do, but also the absolute worst.  If you find yourself thinking this, take a step back and reflect on the entire situation for a while.  Think critically about what’s really happening and how you play a part in it.</span>\n\n**Taking too much ownership – **<span style="font-weight: 400;">On the other hand, you shouldn’t feel the need to take responsibility for every little thing that goes wrong in the relationship.  Wanting to fix things and bring your relationship back to its former glory is natural, but taking on more than your fair share of the blame is unhealthy and will quickly lead your relationship down a dark path.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Be sure that your relationship is balanced, and that both people are able to recognize when they should be taking responsibility.</span>\n\n**Failing to understand the difference between the two – **<span style="font-weight: 400;">The key to finding this balance in your relationship is know when to stand up for yourself and accept the blame, and knowing when to stand up for yourself when you’re not to blame.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">There are going to be many situations during the relationship in which you’re going to want to attack your partner and blame everything on them, but you know that isn’t wise.  But you also recognize that your significant other can’t be consistently getting away with crappy behavior.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Talk with your partner about where you think each of you falls within this spectrum, and really listen to what they have to say.  It might shed some light on a problems you’ve been dealing with.</span>\n\n\n	\N	<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">For those of us who are in committed relationships or who are striving to find that special someone to call our own, happiness is at the top of the priority list.  The thing is, being in a relationship where you both have intense feelings for one another often causes us to act and think in ways that we normally wouldn’t.  </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">So, we’re in love and we’re striving to build a lasting happiness with our significant other, but at the same time we’re also acting a bit crazy because of these strong emotions, and this is where problems arise.  And more often than not, these problems arise because one partner is unknowingly doing things that the other partner doesn’t like.  Because if you kn