1350	6bed7110-2f0a-4785-adbf-e8a479919de9	5 Scientifically Proven Methods to Fall Asleep Faster	5-scientifically-proven-methods-to-fall-asleep-faster	\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Ever find yourself tossing and turning at night, unable to fall asleep no matter how hard you try?  You’re not the only one.  Insomnia is a very real problem; **[the National Institutes of Health](http://nihseniorhealth.gov/sleepandaging/insomnia/01.html)** report that almost half of U.S. adults aged 60 and older suffer from the condition.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Liza Meltzer, education scholar for the National Sleep Foundation and associate professor of pediatrics at National Jewish Health in Denver, says that unless there are specific medical conditions or medications that are keeping you awake at night, the most likely cause of your sleeplessness is anxiety.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">So, if you’re interested in hibernating for a few days and want to do it easily, try these five scientifically-proven methods of falling asleep:</span>\n\n**Get out of bed and do something for at least 10 minutes**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">If you ever find yourself lying awake in bed unable to fall asleep for at least 15 minutes, try getting out of bed and doing something for 10 minutes or so.  Preferably, do an activity that requires the use of your hands and your head, and avoid using any digital screens, as their blue light has been shown to inhibit melatonin production, which is a sleep-inducing hormone.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">**[Richard Wiseman](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cpGoWPrTJho),** professor for the Public Understanding of Psychology at the University of Hertfordshire, says “the key is to avoid associating your bed with being awake.”</span>\n\n**Hide the clock**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Watching every second of time slowly tick down as you lie awake in bed increases stress levels, which in turn makes it more difficult for your nervous system to relax into a slumber.  Easy solution?  Hide your clock and make sure you can’t see what time it is.  Constantly looking to see what time it is only makes things worse.</span>\n\n**Make sure your room is a bit chilly**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">**[According to the Harvard Medical School](http://healthysleep.med.harvard.edu/healthy/science/what/characteristics)**, our bodies dip to lower temperatures when we’re falling asleep, which is believed to help speed up the process of falling asleep.  Having a cooler room makes it easier for your body to fall into the sleep cycle.  Meltzer says the best conditions for falling asleep are “cool, dark, comfortable bedrooms.”</span>\n\n**Take a hot shower before bedtime**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">A nice hot shower before your bedtime helps you fall asleep due to the rapid change in body temperature, from high to low.  Studies have found that because you’re going from a higher temperature to a lower temperature so quickly, your metabolism slows faster and your body preps for sleep more rapidly.</span>\n\n**Wear socks to bed**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">A study published **[in the journal ](http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v401/n6748/abs/401036a0.html)**</span>**[*Nature*](http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v401/n6748/abs/401036a0.html)**<span style="font-weight: 400;"> found that warm feet and hands were indicative of the fast onset of sleep.  The study had participants place a heated water bottle on their feet, effectively widening the blood vessels on the surface of the skin, which allowed for more rapid heat loss.</span>\n\n\n	\N	<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Ever find yourself tossing and turning at night, unable to fall asleep no matter how hard you try?  You’re not the only one.  Insomnia is a very real problem; <strong><a href="http://nihseniorhealth.gov/sleepandaging/insomnia/01.html">the National Institutes of Health</a></strong> report that almost hal