1353	d61bda56-ba46-4559-9f63-d77068981880	5 Signs Your Child is Hiding Anxiety	5-signs-your-child-is-hiding-anxiety	\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Children are typically pretty up front and vocal about the things that are going on in their lives, so you usually don’t have to worry about them stressing over much.  They like to tell you their fears and it’s easy to tell when they’re scared.  Maybe they like to grab hold of you during new or stressful situations.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">While it might seem like you know your child like the back of your hand, they don’t always like to display their anxieties.  Sometimes they’ll keep their fears and anxieties hidden.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Here are five signs to look for if you think your child might be anxious and not telling you:</span>\n\n**Physical Symptoms**\n\n![Anxiety isn't just in the mind, it can be felt in the body as well.](http://blogs.psychcentral.com/anxious-kids/files/2016/03/image.jpeg)\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Anxiety has just as much of an effect on the mind as it does the body.  Some common symptoms in anxious children include nauseated stomachs, gastrointestinal problems, chest pains, headaches, and cheek biting to name a few on the long list.  If you’ve taken your child to medical professionals in search of an answer to their ailments, but have found nothing, it might be anxiety.</span>\n\n**They suddenly don’t like school**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">If your child is suddenly disinterested in school and you’re struggling to even get them there without resistance, anxiety might be to blame.  If they’re consistently feigning sickness only to be completely fine not long after you’ve let them play hookey, anxiety might be to blame.  Look for signs of them being totally fine during the weekends, and symptoms showing up right when school is back in session.</span>\n\n**Anger**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">While kids typically experience anger for a variety of different reasons, which can make identifying the sole cause difficult, it could be anxiety that is causing them to reach their boiling point quicker than usual.  If they’re coming home from school with their fuse already lit or bedtime starts becoming a huge hassle, anxiety might be at the root of the issue.  Be observant of when and why they are getting angry.</span>\n\n**They’re avoiding their normal activities**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">If they’re always trying to stay home instead of going to restaurants or to stores or they’re avoiding activities and situations that they’ve enjoyed in the past, take some time to look into why.  It’s possible that they’ve simply moved on from certain things, but remember that the most common method of coping with anxiety in children is ‘avoidance’.  </span>\n\n**Routines and rituals**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">If your child is practicing rituals or seeks out certain behaviors from others, like needing to be told “I love you” a certain way or a certain number of times before doing something, then they could be harboring anxiety.  While routines are often comforting and predictable, rituals need to be done to perfection, and need to be redone if they are not done correctly the first time.  Routines can be seen as healthy, while rituals are indicative of anxiety.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">If you think your child might be anxious, the sooner they receive help for the better off they will be.  </span>\n\n(h/t **[Psychcentral](http://blogs.psychcentral.com/anxious-kids/2016/03/missed-signs-child-anxiety/)**)\n\n\n	\N	<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Children are typically pretty up front and vocal about the things that are going on in their lives, so you usually don’t have to worry about them stressing over much.  They like to tell you their fears and it’s easy to tell when they’re scared.  Maybe they like to grab hold of you during new or stressful situations.</span></p>\n\n<p>