e getting angry.</span></p>\n\n<p><strong>They’re avoiding their normal activities</strong></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">If they’re always trying to stay home instead of going to restaurants or to stores or they’re avoiding activities and situations that they’ve enjoyed in the past, take some time to look into why.  It’s possible that they’ve simply moved on from certain things, but remember that the most common method of coping with anxiety in children is ‘avoidance’.  </span></p>\n\n<p><strong>Routines and rituals</strong></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">If your child is practicing rituals or seeks out certain behaviors from others, like needing to be told “I love you” a certain way or a certain number of times before doing something, then they could be harboring anxiety.  While routines are often comforting and predictable, rituals need to be done to perfection, and need to be redone if they are not done correctly the first time.  Routines can be seen as healthy, while rituals are indicative of anxiety.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">If you think your child might be anxious, the sooner they receive help for the better off they will be.  </span></p>\n\n<p>(h/t <strong><a href="http://blogs.psychcentral.com/anxious-kids/2016/03/missed-signs-child-anxiety/">Psychcentral</a></strong>)</p>	http://cdn.heartcenteredrebalancing.com/2016/04/feature_image_temsdfgplate.jpg	f	f	published	en_US	public	\N	\N	1	2016-04-12 23:26:11+00	1	2016-04-12 23:26:11+00	1	2016-04-12 23:26:11+00	1
