ntal relaxation.”</span>*\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">So, if you’re struggling to fall asleep or have been suffering from a taxing case of insomnia, try cuddling up next to your favorite furry companion and see if they’ll help you doze off into la-la land.</span>\n\n\n	\N	<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Sleep makes up about a third of our entire lives, yet a lot of us struggle when it comes to doing it well.  <strong><a href="http://bettersleep.org/better-sleep/the-science-of-sleep/sleep-statistics-research/starving-for-sleep-americas-hunger-games/">The Better Sleep Council reports</a></strong> that 8 out of every 10 Americans say that they would “feel better and more prepared for the day if they had an extra hour of sleep.”  </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">I’ve had numerous friends gawk at me when I tell them that I regularly get about 8 hours of sleep each night.  Why?  Because they tend to only get 6 hours a night on average simply due to how busy they are.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">But a recent study by researchers at the <strong><a href="http://www.mayoclinic.org/patient-visitor-guide/arizona">Mayo Clinic</a></strong> have found that many of our traditional problems with sleep can be remedied by sleeping with our furry companions.  </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Of the 150 patients surveyed on sleep habits, 56 percent of them said they shared their bed (or bedroom) with their pets.  Out of these people, 20 percent said that their pets kept them from sleeping, while 41 percent said that having them nearby actually helped them to sleep better.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Single people in particular reported improved sleeping ability when sharing their bed with their pet.  </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The researchers wrote:</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">“</span><em><span style="font-weight: 400;">Respondents described feeling secure, content and relaxed when their pet slept nearby. The value of these experiences, although poorly understood, cannot be dismissed because sleep is dependent on a state of physical and mental relaxation.”</span></em></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">So, if you’re struggling to fall asleep or have been suffering from a taxing case of insomnia, try cuddling up next to your favorite furry companion and see if they’ll help you doze off into la-la land.</span></p>	http://cdn.heartcenteredrebalancing.com/2016/04/feature_image_tedfgsdssdfmplate.jpg	f	f	published	en_US	public	\N	\N	1	2016-04-29 07:28:41+00	1	2016-04-29 07:28:41+00	1	2016-04-29 07:28:41+00	1
1427	b280ee29-b39c-4fa5-a2f7-dfb778890eca	5 Ways To Figure Out Your True Purpose In Life	5-ways-to-figure-out-your-true-purpose-in-life	\nAs humans, one thing that comes naturally to us is the desire to produce, create, or design.  We see our work (and other services that we do) as reflections of ourselves.  We thrive on positive feedback and enjoy doing things that other people love or get excited about.\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Which means that when we can’t find something to be passionate about, or are lacking positive feedback on the work that we’re doing, we suffer in many ways.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">But, we can change our perspective and take full responsibility for our lives.  You can only understand your purpose in life once you genuinely understand who you are as a person.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">And here are five ways to help you get started on this journey:</span>\n\n**List out your positive natural skills and abilities**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Maybe you’re at your best when painting or writing, maybe you excel at helping and healing others, maybe you’re at your best when you’re pushing your body physically–whatever it is, figure out what you’re good at, even if you can’t transform it into a career immediately.</span>\n\n**List out your natural interests or hobbies**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">For me, I’d put down things like: running, hiking, mountain biking, writing, etc.  For you it might be reading books for hours on end, or managing social media connections, or solving difficult problems using math and code.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Your natural interests say a lot about who you are and they’re important to know, because once you piece them all together, you can really start to solve the puzzle.</span>\n\n**See if anything from the first two overlap**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Living your dream life requires a few things: interest, ability, dedication and motivation.  Toss out any one of these and you are not likely to achieve it.  There’s always chance and luck, but they’re too fickle to focus on.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Focus on the things you can control: what do you want, can you do it well, and how are you going to make a living doing it.</span>\n\n**How do you want to be remembered when you leave this world?**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Death is the great equalizer for all of mankind.  So, when your final moments are upon you, do you want your loved ones to remember you for your accomplished career or how often you spent time with family and friends?  Maybe you want them to remember how kind and generous you were, or maybe you don’t want to be remembered at all.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">All of these things can help you figure out what you’re ‘meant’ to do in life.</span>\n\n**Think about things you wouldn’t mind doing every single day if you had to**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Think about your version of a perfect life real quick.  What would you love to spend your time doing every day if you had the choice to do </span>*<span style="font-weight: 400;">anything</span>*<span style="font-weight: 400;">.  Without taking into consideration status, titles, accolades or achievements, how would you live your life?  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Try not to be concerned with how your life looks to others, if this is your focus then you are not living for yourself.</span>\n\nh/t [**Bustle**](http://www.bustle.com/articles/107298-9-ways-to-figure-out-what-youre-meant-to-do)\n\n\n	\N	<p>As humans, one thing that comes naturally to us is the desire to produce, create, or design.  We see our work (and other services that we do) as reflections of ourselves.  We thrive on positive feedback and enjoy doing things that other people love or get excited about.</p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Which means that when we can’t find something to be passionate ab