: 400;">Boost Your Memory Function by 75% by Smelling Rosemary</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;"><strong><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rosemary">Rosemary</a></strong>is a great herb to have around at pretty much all times.  It’s the woody herb that has the pungent, evergreen, needle-like leaves that are typically accompanied by white, pink, purple or blue flowers.  It’s a member of the mint family and its name, translated from Latin, means “dew of the sea.”</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">It’s an herb that has been used in traditional medicines over the generations and now one study has found out a few reasons why:</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Rosemary contains <strong><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carnosic_acid">carnosic acid</a></strong>which is known for combating free radical damage in our brains and in our DNA. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Additionally, researchers found the chemical compound <strong><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eucalyptol">1,8-cineole</a></strong>, which is largely responsible for enhanced memory function.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The study, which has been published in </span><strong><em><a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/02/27/rosemary-brain-memory-18-cineole_n_1304250.html">Therapeutic Advances in Psychopharmacology</a></em></strong><span style="font-weight: 400;">, discovered that rosemary can actually improve memory function by up to 75 percent, simply by smelling it!</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">So, if you’ve never been savvy to the benefits of rosemary, now is the perfect time to pick some up or plant some in your garden!</span></p>	http://cdn.heartcenteredrebalancing.com/2016/05/feature_image_temasdfasplate.jpg	f	f	published	en_US	public	\N	\N	1	2016-05-10 01:39:51+00	1	2016-05-10 01:39:51+00	1	2016-05-10 01:39:51+00	1
