ence and kindness during times of trouble of conflict.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">An easy-going person is the perfect target for the malicious intent of a toxic person seeking to take that easy-going-ness away from them.  They see this way of being as weakness and something to be taken advantage of.</span>\n\n**You strive to see the good in everyone**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Giving people the benefit of the doubt is often a double-edged sword, but we do it anyway because we like to believe that people are inherently good.  And most of the time people live up to this expectation, but every so often we come across an individual that challenges our beliefs.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Wanting to see only the good in people can lead us down dark paths, like when we hold onto relationships thinking that a toxic person will change, even though they continue to put us down and do things to hurt us.</span>\n\n\n	\N	<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Toxic people make their way into our lives for a variety of different reasons, and a lot of the time we’re completely unaware of these reasons.  You might be attracting toxic people without even knowing it.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Here are five ways you might be unintentionally bringing toxic people into your life:</span></p>\n\n<p><strong>You like to be a good listener</strong></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Being a good listener is not a bad trait to have, but it invites toxic people into our lives when they see it as an opportunity to talk at us for hours about themselves.  </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">They like to ignore the subtle gestures you give indicating that you’re done because they’re not too concerned with what you have to say or think in the first place.  Active listeners are often targets of the narcissistic.</span></p>\n\n<p><strong>You’re generous</strong></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Generosity is und