1368	86e6734b-85b1-49de-86f0-c16df8106035	5 Tips to Live By if You're a Highly Sensitive Person	5-tips-to-live-by-if-youre-a-highly-sensitive-person	\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Oftentimes in cultures and societies around the world, sensitive people are tagged with labels like ‘weak’ or ‘unworthy,’ which I think is a very flawed way of thinking.  Being capable of deep, sincere emotion and thought cannot be described as a weakness or vice.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">We should never be afraid to say what we are feeling, whether it be bad or good.  And bottling up emotions isn’t good for anyone.  It leads to isolation and thoughts that you are alone.  You’re not alone.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Psychotherapist and researcher, Dr. Elaine Aron, says that 15 to 20 percent of people have nervous systems that process stimuli more intensely than the average.  Not only do they feel more, but they think more deeply, leading to quick overstimulation.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Here are five tips for the highly sensitive person:</span>\n\n**There is nothing that will ‘fix’ you**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Sensitivity is largely a trait of one’s temperament, not some sort of medical condition.  Because of this, you can’t really say that anything is wrong with you.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">While many doctors and medical professionals might say otherwise, processing sensitivity research is young and undeveloped.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Sensitive people that achieve great things do so because they understand that they are not ‘flawed.’</span>\n\n**Look for other sensitive people like yourself**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Being highly sensitive often makes you feel like you’re alone in your struggles, when that notion couldn’t be further from the truth.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Look for other sensitive people who are already succeeding in their endeavors, as they can offer firsthand knowledge of the things you deal with regularly.</span>\n\n**Strive to find positivity in every encounter or situation you find yourself in**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Highly sensitive people are much more capable of soaking up the energy of their surroundings, meaning negative environments promote negativity and positive environments promote positivity.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">One of the best tactics a sensitive person can learn is how to acknowledge negativity and then let go of it.</span>\n\n**Give yourself the same compassion that you give others**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Highly sensitive people are known for their immense passion.  This often takes the form of them putting the needs and desires of others over their own, while also being highly critical of themselves.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Always be willing to give yourself the same leniency and compassion that you want others to have.</span>\n\n**Do your best not to suffocate your sensitivity**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">One of the easiest things to do is tune out the overwhelming amount of stimuli so that you can appear as though it doesn’t affect you on a deeper level, and this is a very unhealthy practice.  While it might trick your mind for a short time, your sensitive self knows better.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">The sensitive person needs to learn how to free themselves of the constant need for control, so that you can use this energy on other things, like creativity, empathy and happiness.</span>\n\n\n	\N	<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Oftentimes in cultures and societies around the world, sensitive people are tagged with labels like ‘weak’ or ‘unworthy,’ which I think is a very flawed way of thinking.  Being capable of deep, sincere emotion and thought cannot be described as a weakness or vice.  </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">We should never be afraid to say what we are 