1369	ee88f68f-ae1a-4402-bc05-cc786bcf6f83	Silica Gel Bags: 5 Reasons Why You Shouldn't Throw Them Away	silica-gel-bags-5-reasons-why-you-shouldnt-throw-them-away	\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">“DO NOT EAT,” reads the little silica gel bag that just fell out of the pocket of the new jacket that you ordered.  Thanks for the heads up, little bag, because before I had read that, my initial instinct was to ingest a tiny white bag full of little plastic-looking beads.  Usually, a fade away jump-shot into the trashcan is the only time of day I’d give this little bag, but after reading a bit more about them, I’ve started holding onto the little guys.</span>\n\nThese bags aren’t inherently poisonous, which I’m sure many people suspect they are.  They’re simply filled with silicon dioxide, which you shouldn’t eat.  They’re there for you to use them, if you want, and you should.  Here are five good reasons to use them again and again:\n\n**Put them in your gym bag – **<span style="font-weight: 400;">Toss a couple in your gym bag, they’ll absorb the extra moisture that causes that terrible stench.  But what’s even better is that they’ll prevent bacteria from thriving in the damp and moist environment that holds all of your dirty clothes.</span>\n\n**Put them between towels – **<span style="font-weight: 400;">A couple of these in the towel cabinet will keep them from getting damp and smelling like wet dog.  Easy solution.</span>\n\n**They make your razors last longer – **<span style="font-weight: 400;">Grab a plastic container, throw a couple silica bags in there and leave your razor in there after you’re done shaving.  This will help the razor to last longer.</span>\n\n**Save old photos – **<span style="font-weight: 400;">Even those pictures that you’ve preserved forever in time will decay, over time.  If you do not store them correctly they will surely perish.  Put a few silica bags in your box of old photos, and save them from dreaded moisture.</span>\n\n**Save your makeup – **<span style="font-weight: 400;">Ok, now that I have your attention. Just kidding.  A couple of these bags in your makeup purse or box will keep your powdery stuff powdery, rather than curdled.</span>\n\n\n	\N	<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">“DO NOT EAT,” reads the little silica gel bag that just fell out of the pocket of the new jacket that you ordered.  Thanks for the heads up, little bag, because before I had read that, my initial instinct was to ingest a tiny white bag full of little plastic-looking beads.  Usually, a fade away jump-shot into the trashcan is the only time of day I’d give this little bag, but after reading a bit more about them, I’ve started holding onto the little guys.</span></p>\n\n<p>These bags aren’t inherently poisonous, which I’m sure many people suspect they are.  They’re simply filled with silicon dioxide, which you shouldn’t eat.  They’re there for you to use them, if you want, and you should.  Here are five good reasons to use them again and again:</p>\n\n<p><em>*Put them in your gym bag – *</em><span style="font-weight: 400;">Toss a couple in your gym bag, they’ll absorb the extra moisture that causes that terrible stench.  But what’s even better is that they’ll prevent bacteria from thriving in the damp and moist environment that holds all of your dirty clothes.</span></p>\n\n<p><em>*Put them between towels – *</em><span style="font-weight: 400;">A couple of these in the towel cabinet will keep them from getting damp and smelling like wet dog.  Easy solution.</span></p>\n\n<p><em>*They make your razors last longer – *</em><span style="font-weight: 400;">Grab a plastic container, throw a couple silica bags in there and leave your razor in there after you’re done shaving.  This will help the razor to last longer.</span></p>\n\n<p><em>*Save old photos – *</em><span style="font-weight: 400;">Even those pictures that you’ve preserved forever in time will decay, over time.  If you do not store them correctly they will surely perish.