1371	de5d4c1f-d619-4328-9c40-b75d64824cc6	You Need To Read This Teenager’s Empowering Message About Self-Acceptance	you-need-to-read-this-teenagers-empowering-message-about-self-acceptance	\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Sometimes we find ourselves in the company of toxic people.  They make their way into our lives, grab hold and can be difficult to get to let go.  Once they’re finally gone, you’re left wondering, “what the hell was I thinking?”</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">A teenager named Brittaney found herself in just such a situation.  She was in a relationship with a person who loved highlighting all of her flaws, and even allowed him authority over what hairstyles she could wear, what her makeup should look like, and even how heavy she should be.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">This person would use hurtful words like ‘ridiculous,’ ‘tacky,’ and ‘ugly’ to describe Brittaney’s physical appearance.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Why not just leave this person, right?  Sometimes it’s harder than you think, especially when your self-confidence is nonexistent.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Brittaney finally lost all of her confidence when she was dumped for a girl who was “prettier,” as she blamed herself for it happening.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">But this was also a turning point for Brittaney, who, instead of continuing down the harmful path of self-hate and self-harm, as so many others do, decided to use Facebook as her platform for a powerful and inspiring message.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Her message is now going viral with tens of thousands of likes and comments, as so many people can relate with and empathize with the pain that this teen was experiencing.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Read her message below:</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">“You always told me I didn’t look good with long hair and that you preferred girls with short hair. So I kept my hair cut above my shoulders at all times. You laughed at me and told me I looked ridiculous when I dyed my hair red when we were together. So a week later I dyed it back blonde.”</span>\n\n![](http://cdn8.littlethings.com/app/uploads/2016/01/10357268_10202458732455222_527141989_o-600x800.jpg)\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">“You would always point out if I was wearing too much makeup. (Winged eyeliner and mascara most of the time) So I just stopped wearing it. You told me tattoos and piercings were tacky and ugly. And would try to take out my belly button ring every time you saw it. So I took out my piercings and didn’t get any more tattoos.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">You pointed out my stretch marks every chance you got. So I did my best to keep them hidden.”</span>\n\n![](http://cdn7.littlethings.com/app/uploads/2016/01/fdfe-600x375.jpg)\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">“You pointed out every time I looked like I had gained weight. So I started eating less every day. You pointed out every single flaw I had. So I lost every bit of confidence I had.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">I did everything I could to be what you wanted. I did everything you told me to do. It still wasn’t good enough. You left me for a younger prettier girl. Someone you could mold and shape into what you wanted. Like you tried to do with me. And up until a few months ago I blamed myself for everything that happened. You blamed me too.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">But finally I started to see the truth.”</span>\n\n![](http://cdn6.littlethings.com/app/uploads/2016/01/12345430_992020954197252_7998749501399407_n-600x536.jpg)\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">“You weren’t out of my league. I was out of yours. I wasn’t the one who wasn’t good enough for you.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">You were the one who wasn’t good enough for me. You couldn’t accept me for who I was. When I took you the way you were.”</span>\n\n![](http://cdn4.littlethings.com/app/uploads/2016/01/Screen-Shot-2016-01-26-at-3-600x447.jpg)\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">“So now here I am a few months later. My hair is past my shoulders. My hair is bright red. I’ve got a new tattoo. New piercings. Started wearing makeup again. I eat whatever I want whenever I want and weigh 135 pounds. I still have my stretch marks.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">And I’ve finally gotten my confidence back. I finally see myself looking back at me when I look in the mirror. It’s so hard for me to come out about this and admit that I became so vulnerable because of one guy. Something I always said would never happen. It’s humiliating to even think about how low I got. But what gives me the guts to come out about this is the fact that I overcame it and I’m finally back to who I really am.”</span>\n\nWhat do you think of Brittaney’s message?  Have you ever broken out of a terrible situation, feeling empowered and strong, as you came out on the other side?\n\n\n	\N	<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Sometimes we find ourselves in the company of toxic people.  They make their way into our lives, grab hold and can be difficult to get to let go.  Once they’re finally gone, you’re left wondering, “what the hell was I thinking?”</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">A teenager named Brittaney found herself in just such a situation.  She was in a relationship with a person who loved highlighting all of her flaws, and even allowed him authority over what hairstyles she could wear, what her makeup should look like, and even how heavy she should be.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">This person would use hurtful words like ‘ridiculous,’ ‘tacky,’ and ‘ugly’ to describe Brittaney’s physical appearance.  </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Why not just leave this person, right?  Sometimes it’s harder than you think, especially when your self-confidence is nonexistent.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">B