1374	300639ac-9453-4a1c-a410-0c87c4d5ad61	5 Signs You're Gluten Intolerant	5-signs-youre-gluten-intolerant	\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">It seems like the term “gluten-free” randomly popped into mainstream culture not that long ago, with many people claiming that a sensitivity to gluten, a protein that is found in wheat, barley, and rye, causes them to suffer gastrointestinal problems, joint pain, fatigue, and even depression.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">While some have written the condition off as simply a new fad among dieters and nutritionists, it is very real.  In fact, celiac disease, which is the most serious type of gluten intolerance, **[occurs in 1 out of every 100 people](https://celiac.org/celiac-disease/what-is-celiac-disease/)** across the globe.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Here are five signs that you have a gluten intolerance:</span>\n\n**Unexpected weight gain**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">If you’ve suddenly packed on some pounds without any changes to diet or exercise, you might be gluten intolerant.  Weight gain from a gluten intolerance happens because of two reasons: malabsorption and gut permeability (two side effects of gluten intolerance), and the onset of systemic inflammation, which is caused by gluten.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Avoid gluten for a while and see if your weight goes back to normal.</span>\n\n**Headaches and Migraines**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Migraines and headaches have been found to be much more common in those who are gluten intolerant.  In fact, a study looking at a gluten sensitive group of people found that 56 percent of them suffered from chronic headaches and migraines, compared to 14 percent of the control group.</span>\n\n**Fatigue / Exhaustion**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">While research regarding the effect that gluten has on fatigue and exhaustion is scarce, many medical professionals believe that a gluten intolerance can cause these effects through inflammation and de-allocation of the body’s energy reserves.</span>\n\n**Skin Problems**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Skin problems can arise from a gluten intolerance because of its aforementioned malabsorption traits that affect various different areas of our bodies.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">**[Gluten has been correlated](http://www.coreonehealth.com/gluten-sensitivity-and-female-hormones)**with acne, psoriasis, eczema, and dermatitis herpetiformis (DH).  Symptoms can include burning sensations, redness, rashes, itchiness and sometimes blistering.</span>\n\n**Dental Problems**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">A study published in </span>*<span style="font-weight: 400;">BMS Gastroenterology</span>*<span style="font-weight: 400;"> found a link between gluten sensitivity and “aphthous stomatitis,” which is a condition that exhibits recurring mouth ulcers and canker sores.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Additionally, because of gluten’s malabsorption properties, calcium levels are often lowered, resulting in poor dental health.</span>\n\n\n	\N	<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">It seems like the term “gluten-free” randomly popped into mainstream culture not that long ago, with many people claiming that a sensitivity to gluten, a protein that is found in wheat, barley, and rye, causes them to suffer gastrointestinal problems, joint pain, fatigue, and even depression.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">While some have written the condition off as simply a new fad among dieters and nutritionists, it is very real.  In fact, celiac disease, which is the most serious type of gluten intolerance, <strong><a href="https://celiac.org/celiac-disease/what-is-celiac-disease/">occurs in 1 out of every 100 people</a></strong> across the globe.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Here are five signs that you have a gluten intolerance:</span></p>\n\n<p><strong>Unexpected weight gain</strong></p>\n\n<p><span st