1396	c1ec325d-2025-419f-932f-ad79acf5a9d8	4 Things That Only the Extroverted Introvert Understands	4-things-that-only-the-extroverted-introvert-understands	\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">You always hear about people getting labeled as either ‘extroverted,’ meaning they’re outgoing, spontaneous, social-loving people, or ‘introverted,’ which means pretty much the exact opposite.  Introverts are the people who prefer alone-time to social-time.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">But, if you’re like me and feel that neither of those categories describe you, then you might fall somewhere in between.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Here are four things that only us introverted extroverts will truly understand:</span>\n\n**Talking to strangers is fine, small talk is not**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Holding a conversation hasn’t ever been a problem for you, but when the conversation lulls into anything other than deep and engaging stimulus, you’re quick steer it back in the right direction.  Small talk is fine and all, but you don’t get to know a person through small talk.</span>\n\n**If you’re uncomfortable in a group, you quietly sink into the background**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Being in a highly social setting with lots of people is fine for you, when you know them.  But being around a group of folks that are different than what you’re used to can make you feel awkward and anxious, so you tend to stay quiet and go with the flow rather than try to make an impact.</span>\n\n**You’re constantly in your head**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">The introverted extrovert’s brain is constantly churning, thinking about seemingly random things that largely have nothing to do with what’s happening in the moment.  It could be something that’s happening next week or something you forgot to do at home, or even some other, entirely fantastical daydream.</span>\n\n**Liking alone-time doesn’t mean you enjoy being lonely**\n\n<span style="font-we