g about seemingly random things that largely have nothing to do with what’s happening in the moment.  It could be something that’s happening next week or something you forgot to do at home, or even some other, entirely fantastical daydream.</span></p>\n\n<p><strong>Liking alone-time doesn’t mean you enjoy being lonely</strong></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Being alone by choice is a great thing. Being alone because you have no one who cares to spend time with you is not such a great thing.  Enjoying some ‘me time’ is always great.  You get to do the things you love and make you happy.  But you also love being with people who make you happy.  Which makes being lonely the worst, as you have neither of these things.</span></p>	http://cdn.heartcenteredrebalancing.com/2016/05/feature_image_te44444545mplate-1.jpg	f	f	published	en_US	public	\N	\N	1	2016-05-22 07:14:35+00	1	2016-05-22 07:14:35+00	1	2016-05-22 07:14:35+00	1
1397	81755ac5-ad64-4517-ada0-9f13b0586742	5 Signs You’re In An Emotionally Abusive Relationship	5-signs-youre-in-an-emotionally-abusive-relationship	\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">When we enter into a relationship, abuse is the last thing on our mind.  Because we don’t expect this person, who has committed his or herself to a relationship, to want to damage it in any way.  But, for whatever reasons, we still find ourselves in both emotionally and physically abusive relationships.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Unlike physical abuse, which leaves its mark on the body for all to see, emotional abuse wounds us in more profound ways, ways that often go unnoticed.  And it’s just as easy to be the abuser as it is to be the abused.  Recognizing emotionally abusive habits are key to stopping them altogether.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Here are five signs that emotional abuse is taking place:</span>\n\n**Being publicly shamed**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">In general, degrading someone’s worth is a poor and unacceptable behavior, and doing it in a public setting makes it that much worse.  Helpful criticism is one thing, but insulting a person due to shortcomings or mistakes is inhuman and wrong.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Being publicly shamed increases the emotional damage done tenfold.  </span>\n\n**Constant Disapproval**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">If your partner is seemingly never satisfied (or visibly dissatisfied) with everything you do, this habit can quickly turn into a form of emotional abuse.  You start to question everything that you do, and even change your way of doing things to try to please your partner.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Eventually you will learn that there is nothing you can do or change to make them happy, leading to a degenerated sense of self-worth.</span>\n\n**Using jokes to mask insults**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">I feel like most people have a friend or know someone who uses jokes and half-truths to subtly insult or demean others.  Being able to laugh at yourself is a good trait to have, but allowing someone to degrade you in a way that seems affable is not okay.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Sometimes they don’t even realize they’re doing it, however, that does not make it acceptable behavior.</span>\n\n**Seeking retribution**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Everyone makes mistakes and messes up every now and then, it’s part of being human.  So, actively seeking a form of ‘revenge’ for something that your partner did wrong is unhealthy.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Imposing guilt, lashing out, or simply ignoring your partner out of spite is not fair to either person.  Mistakes will be made, learn how to handle your emotions effectively.</span>\n\n**Constant attempts at belittlement**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">This is easily one of the worst forms of emotional abuse.  If your partner always takes the time to belittle you and make you feel inferior to them, you should probably move on.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">These people love to remind you just how lucky you are to even be with them, or how unworthy of their love you are.  This most likely happens because of insecurities; fearing that you will realize how terrible they truly are and leave.</span>\n\n\n	\N	<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">When we enter into a relationship, abuse is the last thing on our mind.  Because we don’t expect this person, who has committed his or herself to a relationship, to want to damage it in any way.  But, for whatever reasons, we still find ourselves in both emotionally and physically abusive relationships.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Unlike physical abuse, which leaves its mark on the body for all to see, emotional abuse wounds us in more profound ways, ways that often go unnoticed.  And it’s just as easy to be the abuser as it is to be the abused.  Recogni