1399	16ca6aa9-64bc-4ee4-a93e-4a1658bdf036	I Had No Idea THIS is What the Extra Shoelace Hole Was For...Good To Know!	i-had-no-idea-this-is-what-the-extra-shoelace-hole-was-for-good-to-know	\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Growing up, every time I got a new pair of shoes, I noticed that there was always an extra top shoelace hole that rests behind that one that you actually use.  “Why would anyone want to lace their shoes all the way up here?” I always wondered.  Well, it turns out that that hole actually serves a function.  Yeah, it’s not simply another hole for you to get creative with your lacing.</span>\n\nYou’ll find that almost all running and hiking shoes have this extra mystery shoelace hole, and the video below will show you exactly how to utilize it.  They’re typically used to prevent blisters on your heels by stopping your foot from getting jammed at the toe.\n\n<iframe allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" height="658" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/IijQyX_YCKA?feature=oembed" width="1170"></iframe>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Tying your laces with this “heel lock” or “lace lock” method creates friction between the laces at the top of the shoe, closest to the ankle.  What this effectively does is tighten the heel/ankle area without you having to re-tighten the entire shoe.  </span>\n\nTo achieve this lacing technique, begin by inserting the lace in backwards through the top hole so that you have a small loop on either side of your shoe.  Then, cross your laces and insert them each into the loop on the opposite side and tighten them.  Remember to go down and not up, as cinching upward leaves the loop hanging out of the shoe, which you do not want.  Pulling downward creates that tight, locking feel that we want.  Finish by tying your shoe as your normally would and then you’re off!\n\nh/t **[Sun Gazing](http://www.sun-gazing.com/extra-shoelace-hole-used-wish-knew-earlier/)**\n\n\n	\N	<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Growing up, every time I got a