1412	5b420cf4-5130-4d2b-bebb-2103e2de8902	How to Make 100% Homemade Real Fruit Rollups	how-to-make-100-homemade-real-fruit-rollups	\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">As more and more evidence surfaces that processed sugars are absolutely terrible for the human body, people are starting to look for natural alternatives to their favorite snacks and foods.  Fruit Rollups are one such food that are quite popular with both adults and children, but that also contain corn syrup and different acetates and several food colorings; all things that we want to avoid when consuming sugar.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Naturally occurring sugars, like the ones that are found in fruits and vegetables, are what the body really wants.  Many of us have cravings for sweets, which is fine, as long as they’re low in sugar and carbs, right?</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">The ingredients used in the following recipe for homemade fruit rollups are as follows: organic fresh, dried and frozen fruits.  That’s what we like to see.</span>\n\n**The Recipe – 100% Fruit Rollups via [Green Kitchen Stories](http://www.greenkitchenstories.com/fruit-rolls/)**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Pick whichever fruits you would like, fresh, frozen or dried.  Try out some of the recommended combinations below and also experiment with some that you think would be tasty.  Easy to make and quick to set, these will quickly become a household favorite.</span>\n\n- ****Mix the fruit.. **<span style="font-weight: 400;">Into a puree.  Place your fruits into a pot on the stove to warm them and then mix them until they’re in a puree form. If you don’t want seeds in the rollups, use a sieve to remove them.</span>**\n\n- **Spread your puree.. **<span style="font-weight: 400;">Onto a baking mat or parchment paper that has been covered with an oil-based cooking spray (if you don’t coat them with some sort of non-stick, they still get stuck and be incredibly hard to remove).  Use one and a half cups of fruit puree and spread it onto the sheet.  Place in the oven at 140 degrees Fahrenheit (or the lowest heat setting possible).  Prop open the oven door just a tad to let moisture escape.</span>\n\n- **They’re done.. **<span style="font-weight: 400;">When the puree on the sheet isn’t sticky.  This typically takes anywhere from 5 to 8 hours depending on the oven and the types of fruits you used.</span>\n\n- **Cut them with.. **<span style="font-weight: 400;">A sharp pizza cutter or knife and then roll them up in the wax or parchment paper while they’re still fairly warm.</span>\n\n- **Enjoy!**\n\n**Combo Ideas:**\n\n**Yellow – **<span style="font-weight: 400;">Juice from 1 freshly squeezed orange, 200g of dried apricots, and 1 fresh mango</span>\n\n**Purple – **<span style="font-weight: 400;">Frozen blackberries, raspberries and 1 banana (typically a lot of seeds, use blueberries instead if you don’t want the seeds)</span>\n\n**Green – **<span style="font-weight: 400;">Kiwi, mango and mint leaves</span>\n\n**Blue – **<span style="font-weight: 400;">Grape juice and blueberries</span>\n\n**Red – **<span style="font-weight: 400;">The classic! Strawberries and bananas, yum.</span>\n\n![](http://www.loveumadly.comhttp://cdn.heartcenteredrebalancing.com/2012/04/fruit-roll-up1-1024x680.jpg "fruit roll-up")\n\n![](http://www.loveumadly.comhttp://cdn.heartcenteredrebalancing.com/2012/04/fruit-roll-up-2-680x1024.jpg "fruit roll-up 2")\n\n![](http://www.loveumadly.comhttp://cdn.heartcenteredrebalancing.com/2012/04/fruit-roll-up-3-1024x680.jpg "fruit roll-up 3")\n\n \n\n \n\n \n\n \n\n \n\n \n\n \n\n![](http://www.loveumadly.comhttp://cdn.heartcenteredrebalancing.com/2012/04/fruit-roll-up-8-1024x680.jpg "fruit roll-up 8")\n\n\n	\N	<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">As more and more evidence surfaces that processed sugars are absolutely terrible for the human body, people are starting to look for natural alternatives to their favorite snacks and foods.  Fruit Rollups are one such food that are quite popular with both adults and children, but that also contain corn syrup and different acetates and several food colorings; all things that we want to avoid when consuming sugar.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Naturally occurring sugars, like the ones that are found in fruits and vegetables, are what the body really wants.  Many of us have cravings for sweets, which is fine, as long as they’re low in sugar and carbs, right?</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The ingredients used in the following recipe for homemade fruit rollups are as follows: organic fresh, dried and frozen fruits.  That’s what we like to see.</span></p>\n\n<p><strong>The Recipe – 100% Fruit Rollups via <a href="http://www.greenkitchenstories.com/fruit-rolls/">Green Kitchen Stories</a></strong></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Pick whichever fruits you would like, fresh, frozen or dried.  Try out some of the recommended combinations below and also experiment with some that you think would be tasty.  Easy to make and quick to set, these will quickly become a household favorite.</span></p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><p><strong><em>*Mix the fruit.. *</em><span style="font-weight: 400;">Into a puree.  Place your fruits into a pot on the stove to warm them and then mix them until they’re in a puree form. If you don’t want seeds in the rollups, use a sieve to remove them.</span></strong></p></li>\n<li><p><em>*Spread your puree.. *</em><span style="font-weight: 400;">Onto a baking mat or parchment paper that has been covered with an oil-based cooking spray (if you don’t coat them with some sort of non-stick, they still get stuck and be incredibly hard to remove).  Use one and a half cups of fruit puree and spread it onto the sheet.  Place in the oven at 140 degrees Fahrenheit (or the lowest heat setting possible).  Prop open the oven door just a tad to let moisture escape.</span></p></li>\n<li><p><em>*They’re done.. *</em><span style="font-weight: 400;">When the puree on the sheet isn’t sticky.  This typically takes anywhere from 5 to 8 hours depending on the oven and the types of fruits you used.</span></p></li>\n<li><p><em>*Cut them with.. *</em><span style="font-weight: 400;">A sharp pizza cutter or knife and then roll them up in the wax or parchment paper while they’re still fairly warm.</span></p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Enjoy!</strong></p></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>Combo Ideas:</strong></p>\n\n<p><em>*Yellow – *</em><span style="font-weight: 400;">Juice from 1 freshly squeezed orange, 200g of dried apricots, and 1 fresh mango</span></p>\n\n<p><em>*Purple – *</em><span style="font-weight: 400;">Frozen blackberries, raspberries and 1 banana (typically a lot of seeds, use blueberries instead if you don’t want the seeds)</span></p>\n\n<p><em>*Green – *</em><span style="font-weight: 400;">Kiwi, mango and mint leaves</span></p>\n\n<p><em>*Blue – *</em><span style="font-weight: 400;">Grape juice and blueberries</span></p>\n\n<p><em>*Red – *</em><span style="font-weight: 400;">The classic! Strawberries and bananas, yum.</span></p>\n\n<p><img src="http://www.loveumadly.comhttp://cdn.heartcenteredrebalancing.com/2012/04/fruit-roll-up1-1024x680.jpg "fruit roll-up"" alt="" /></p>\n\n<p><img src="http://www.loveumadly.comhttp://cdn.heartcenteredrebalancing.com/2012/04/fruit-roll-up-2-680x1024.jpg "fruit roll-up 2"" alt="" /></p>\n\n<p><img src="http://www.loveumadly.comhttp://cdn.heartcenteredrebalancing.com/2012/04/fruit-roll-up-3-1024x680.jpg "fruit roll-up 3"" alt="" /></p>\n\n<p><img src="http://www.loveumadly.comhttp://cdn.heartcenteredrebalancing.com/2012/04/fruit-roll-up-8-1024x680.jpg "fruit roll-up 8"" alt="" /></p>	http://cdn.heartcenteredrebalancing.com/2016/06/feature_imadsasd3ge_template.jpg	f	f	published	en_US	public	\N	\N	1	2016-06-02 06:32:40+00	1	2016-06-02 06:32:40+00	1	2016-06-02 06:32:40+00	1
