1420	c17ecc20-a25d-4676-9969-9d2ebc683a95	The Easiest Way Ever to Grow Tomato Seedlings	the-easiest-way-ever-to-grow-tomato-seedlings	\nIf you’ve recently been wanting to grow your own fruits and veggies, but aren’t sure where to get started, tomato seedlings can be one of the best places to start.  And all you need are some overripe tomatoes you might have sitting in the fridge right now.\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">While you probably don’t want to eat these overripe tomatoes, they </span>*<span style="font-weight: 400;">can</span>*<span style="font-weight: 400;"> be used to grow new seedlings, and eventually new, tasty tomatoes.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">The video below, created by The Wannabe Homesteader, shows exactly how we can grow tomatoes using nothing but a pot, potting soil and one tomato.  Not to mention a little bit of TLC from Mother Nature.</span>\n\n<iframe allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" height="658" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/cLfpeUtyDII?feature=oembed" width="1170"></iframe>\n\n**First,**<span style="font-weight: 400;"> cut your tomato up into quarter-inch thick slices.  Throw these on to a pot of compost and cover them with potting soil or more compost until the tomatoes are just barely covered.  Proceed to water the pot spontaneously over the course of 7 to 14 days.  This should yield about 50 to 60 seedlings.  Find the largest seedlings in the pot, pull them out and plant them in a separate pot using only two plants per pot.  Et voila!</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">The **[Yale Environment 360](http://e360.yale.edu/)**organization reports that 30 to 40 percent of everything grown and raised in the United States each year is thrown away or rots in farms and kitchens.  This ends up being about 133 </span>*<span style="font-weight: 400;">billion</span>*<span style="font-weight: 400;"> pounds of food.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">So, before throwing out your old tomatoes, try your hand at growing some yourself.  It’s a fun little project that requires minimal effort, but yields great reward!</span>\n\n\n	\N	<p>If you’ve recently been wanting to grow your own fruits and veggies, but aren’t sure where to get started, tomato seedlings can be one of the best places to start.  And all you need are some overripe tomatoes you might have sitting in the fridge right now.</p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">While you probably don’t want to eat these overripe tomatoes, they </span><em><span style="font-weight: 400;">can</span></em><span style="font-weight: 400;"> be used to grow new seedlings, and eventually new, tasty tomatoes.  </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The video below, created by The Wannabe Homesteader, shows exactly how we can grow tomatoes using nothing but a pot, potting soil and one tomato.  Not to mention a little bit of TLC from Mother Nature.</span></p>\n\n<iframe allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" height="658" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/cLfpeUtyDII?feature=oembed" width="1170"></iframe>\n\n<p><strong>First,</strong><span style="font-weight: 400;"> cut your tomato up into quarter-inch thick slices.  Throw these on to a pot of compost and cover them with potting soil or more compost until the tomatoes are just barely covered.  Proceed to water the pot spontaneously over the course of 7 to 14 days.  This should yield about 50 to 60 seedlings.  Find the largest seedlings in the pot, pull them out and plant them in a separate pot using only two plants per pot.  Et voila!</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The <strong><a href="http://e360.yale.edu/">Yale Environment 360</a></strong>organization reports that 30 to 40 percent of everything grown and raised in the United States each year is thrown away or rots in farms and kitchens.  This ends up being about 133 </span><em><span style="font-weight: 400;">billion</span></em><span style="font-weight: 400;"> pounds of food.  </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="fon