1421	68a636a7-9ba3-41fd-81e8-83700edbc179	You've Been Cleaning Your Oven Wrong This Whole Time	youve-been-cleaning-your-oven-wrong-this-whole-time	\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Kitchens get dirty quick.  They’re supposed to, right?  It’s where you make all of the delicious food for yourself and friends and family.  It’s where people like to gather in anticipation, socializing and catching up while their mouths water at the thought of the feast that is to come.  </span>\n\nUnfortunately, this also means that it’s one of the most dirtiest places in the house.  I’m looking at my stovetop area right now, and it’s not pretty.  Pieces of cooked scrambled egg are scattered here and there, oil grease from bacon and breakfast sausage coats just about every square inch of the surface, and I haven’t the slightest bit of motivation to clean it right now.\n\nBut what’s even scarier is what I can’t see, and that’s inside the oven.  Ovens are notoriously tedious to clean.  You’ve got to get all up in there with your cleaner and scrubber and put in some serious work to get that thing nice and clean.  And at the end of the day, it’s the last thing you want to do.\n\nSo, here’s an easy way to clean that bad boy up:\n\nGrab a bowl, a rag, some water, a spray bottle, a bit of **[baking soda](http://www.allyou.com/budget-home/live-green-save/baking-soda)**, and **[vinegar](http://www.bhg.com/homekeeping/house-cleaning/tips/cleaning-with-vinegar/)**.  These are the things you will need to get your oven looking clean and shiny.\n\nNow, remove everything from the oven, specifically the racks.\n\nUsing your bowl, mix two tablespoons of baking soda into the water, so that it makes a kind of paste that should be easy to apply and spread around.\n\nUsing the rag (or your hands), apply your mixture to the areas of the oven that need to be cleaned the most.  This should turn your mixture a brown color, but that’s fine.  Once you’ve applied the mixture to all of the bad spots, let it sit overnight for at least twelve hours.\n\nAfter you’ve done the previous step, use a wet rag to wipe down as much baking soda as you can.\n\nFill your spray bottle with the vinegar and then spray it over the areas that you applied baking soda to.\n\nRinse off your wet rag and continue to clean the surfaces.\n\nPut the oven racks back into the oven and then turn the oven on low for about fifteen minutes, so as to dry the inside.\n\nFinally, re-do steps one through six to clean the window area, except let it sit for about half an hour instead of twelve hours before you start wiping everything down.\n\nAnd voila!  You’ve got a relatively easy, safe and effective new way to clean that nasty oven.  And you didn’t have to slave away into the wee hours of the morning to do it.\n\n\n	\N	<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Kitchens get dirty quick.  They’re supposed to, right?  It’s where you make all of the delicious food for yourself and friends and family.  It’s where people like to gather in anticipation, socializing and catching up while their mouths water at the thought of the feast that is to come.  </span></p>\n\n<p>Unfortunately, this also means that it’s one of the most dirtiest places in the house.  I’m looking at my stovetop area right now, and it’s not pretty.  Pieces of cooked scrambled egg are scattered here and there, oil grease from bacon and breakfast sausage coats just about every square inch of the surface, and I haven’t the slightest bit of motivation to clean it right now.</p>\n\n<p>But what’s even scarier is what I can’t see, and that’s inside the oven.  Ovens are notoriously tedious to clean.  You’ve got to get all up in there with your cleaner and scrubber and put in some serious work to get that thing nice and clean.  And at the end of the day, it’s the last thing you want to do.</p>\n\n<p>So, here’s an easy way to clean that bad boy up:</p>\n\n<p>Grab a bowl, a rag, some water, a spray bottle, a bit of <strong><a href="http://www.allyou.com/budget-home/li