1458	880dd4c8-2bdc-4dc0-9c3a-0d3097c2b2ed	One Major U.S. City Is Requiring All Pet Stores to Sell Only Rescues	one-major-u-s-city-is-requiring-all-pet-stores-to-sell-only-rescues	\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Phoenix, Arizona, joined the **[official list of U.S. cities](http://www.bizjournals.com/phoenix/news/2015/07/31/puppies-n-love-owner-expects-to-appeal-ruling-on.html)** that are working to pass legislation focused on shutting down the operation of puppy mills.  And they’re doing it by **[requiring all pet stores to only offer dogs that have been rescued](https://www.thedodo.com/puppy-mills-take-a-hit-1023432625.html)**.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">This comes following the **[upholding of a 2013 ordinance](http://www.azcentral.com/story/news/local/phoenix/2015/07/29/phoenix-outlaw-some-pet-sales-commercial-breeders-approved-judge/30861879/)** that banned the sales of puppies and kittens at pet stores, requiring adoption services for rescues and shelter animals instead.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">So far, the list that Phoenix joins consists of over **[59 different cities and counties](https://www.thedodo.com/puppy-mills-take-a-hit-1023432625.html)** all over the United States, each one working to pass legislation similar to Phoenix’s.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">If you’ve never heard of puppy mills, they’re basically businesses that have intense, and often inhumane, breeding practices.  **[Profit from their puppies](https://www.thedodo.com/puppy-mill-doodles-975608564.html)** comes at a price, however, one that is paid in full by the well-being of the puppies themselves, as well as the dogs being used to breed them.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">The dogs that breed these puppies are typically **[caged their whole lives](https://www.thedodo.com/rescued-dogs-had-never-even-felt-grass-before-1274048102.html)**; rarely, if ever, receiving love or affection.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Phoenix’s decision is celebrated by groups like the **[Humane Society of the United States](http://www.humanesociety.org/?credit=web_id424367309?referrer=http://www.humanesociety.org/search/search-results.html?q=phoenix)**, alongside a number of pet owners and animal activists who wish to see this practice finished.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">While some pet store owners are upset with the legislation, claiming that it will hurt business, it cannot be overlooked that this policy will help prevent the deaths of millions of animals who get euthanized each year, instead of going to a good home.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">What do you think about this legislation? Do you think people should be buying puppies or adopting rescues?</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">And don’t forget to share with your friends and family!</span>\n\n\n	\N	<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Phoenix, Arizona, joined the <strong><a href="http://www.bizjournals.com/phoenix/news/2015/07/31/puppies-n-love-owner-expects-to-appeal-ruling-on.html">official list of U.S. cities</a></strong> that are working to pass legislation focused on shutting down the operation of puppy mills.  And they’re doing it by <strong><a href="https://www.thedodo.com/puppy-mills-take-a-hit-1023432625.html">requiring all pet stores to only offer dogs that have been rescued</a></strong>.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">This comes following the <strong><a href="http://www.azcentral.com/story/news/local/phoenix/2015/07/29/phoenix-outlaw-some-pet-sales-commercial-breeders-approved-judge/30861879/">upholding of a 2013 ordinance</a></strong> that banned the sales of puppies and kittens at pet stores, requiring adoption services for rescues and shelter animals instead.  </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">So far, the list that Phoenix joins consists of over <strong><a href="https://www.thedodo.com/puppy-mills-take-a-hit-1023432625.html">59 different cities and counties</a></strong> all over the United States, each one working to pass legislation similar to Phoenix’s.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">If you’ve never heard of puppy mills, they’re basically businesses that have intense, and often inhumane, breeding practices.  <strong><a href="https://www.thedodo.com/puppy-mill-doodles-975608564.html">Profit from their puppies</a></strong> comes at a price, however, one that is paid in full by the well-being of the puppies themselves, as well as the dogs being used to breed them.  </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The dogs that breed these puppies are typically <strong><a href="https://www.thedodo.com/rescued-dogs-had-never-even-felt-grass-before-1274048102.html">caged their whole lives</a></strong>; rarely, if ever, receiving love or affection.  </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Phoenix’s decision is celebrated by groups like the <strong><a href="http://www.humanesociety.org/?credit=web_id424367309?referrer=http://www.humanesociety.org/search/search-results.html?q=phoenix">Humane Society of the United States</a></strong>, alongside a number of pet owners and animal activists who wish to see this practice finished.  </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">While some pet store owners are upset with the legislation, claiming that it will hurt business, it cannot be overlooked that this policy will help prevent the deaths of millions of animals who get euthanized each year, instead of going to a good home.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">What do you think about this legislation? Do you think people should be buying puppies or adopting rescues?</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">And don’t forget to share with your friends and family!</span></p>	http://cdn.heartcenteredrebalancing.com/2016/07/feature_image_tesdfgsdfgsdfmplate.jpg	f	f	published	en_US	public	\N	\N	1	2016-07-10 07:44:20+00	1	2016-07-10 07:44:20+00	1	2016-07-10 07:44:20+00	1
1422	8854528b-4703-4d3a-8370-6da0593687b7	Los Angeles is Turning Old Motels Into 500 Apartments for Homeless Vets	los-angeles-is-turning-old-motels-into-500-apartments-for-homeless-vets	\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">If you’ve been to Los Angeles in the past five years or so, then you know just how much of a homeless problem the city has.  What’s even worse is that so many of these homeless folks are veterans who once served our country.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">In an effort to house these homeless veterans, the City of Los Angeles has a new plan to renovate old motels and hospitals, turning them into 500 new apartments for homeless veterans.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">How will it work?  First, developers purchase the rundown properties and build them into the efficiency apartments discussed above.  Then, homeless veterans will use vouchers, gained from the **[Department of Veteran Affairs](http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-motel-homeless-conversions-20160527-snap-story.html)**, to pay for their rent.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">The vouchers given to the homeless vets expire after 15 years, and the deal is set up so that landlords will earn a profit as well.  Not to mention, residents of these abodes are eligible for supportive services like case management and counseling.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">This is easily recognizable as a step in the right direction after learning, from the Los Angeles Homeless Services Authority, that there were **[2,733 homeless veterans](https://documents.lahsa.org/Planning/homelesscount/2015/factsheet/LACity.pdf)** on any given night in the city last year.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">“Instead of allowing blighted properties to decay, let’s use them to make powerful change in our communities by giving our veterans the access to services and housing that they need and deserve,” Mayor Eric Garcetti said in a statement.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weigh