1417	1abe6258-632f-4bf5-9e92-b7c8cf5db2c9	256-Year-Old Man Reveals the Secrets of the World Just Before His Death	256-year-old-man-reveals	\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Have you ever wondered what it might be like to live for hundreds of years?  While it’s almost impossible to fathom what events of the world are yet to come, living well over a hundred or even two-hundred years is something that I often think about; mainly because I want to be around to see the future of mankind.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">While I most likely will not live to be past 100 (150 with modern science </span>*<span style="font-weight: 400;">maybe</span>*<span style="font-weight: 400;">) years old, there is one man in history who lived to be older than 250! </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;"> A 1930 New York Times article details the story of a man named Li Ching Yuen, which Imperial Chinese government documents have been found congratulating him on his 150th birthday in 1827, and then on his 200th birthday in 1877.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">A New York Times correspondent noted that, in Li’s neighborhood were old men whose grandfathers knew Li when they were young boys, and that he was a grown man when they knew him.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Tales of Li that are widely accepted in his province say that he was able to read and write as a child, and by ten years of age had traveled to Kansu, Shansi, Tibet, Annam, Siam and Manchuria to gather herbs.  He would gather herbs for 100 years before finally starting a small business where he sold the herbs he once gathered.</span>\n\n**He wasn’t the oldest man to have lived, though**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to Li’s disciples, Li once came across a man who had lived to be 500 years old.  This man taught him Qigong exercises and the diet that would help Li to live for extended periods of time. </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">But on his deathbed, Li is quoted saying, “I have done all that I have to do in this world.”  </span>\n\n**The secret to perpetual health**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Li’s only advice when asked about his secret to a long life was this: “Keep a quiet heart, sit like a tortoise, walk sprightly like a pigeon and sleep like a dog.”  These were the same words Li gave Wu Pei-Fu, the warlord who invited Li to his home, so that he might learn his ways.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Li believed that looking inward, working to create a sense of calm and peacefulness through meditation and breathing techniques were the secret to incredible health.  Essentially, it is your state of mind.</span>\n\n**Hard to believe?**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Yes, this knowledge at face value will have most people skeptical, as we in the Western world have average lifespans of about 70-85 years.  The difference that we must keep in mind when pondering these ideas is that not everyone on this planet has devoted themselves to a 9 to 5 working world lifestyle.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">They aren’t plagued with debt, they aren’t living in crowded polluted cities, and they’re using their bodies to work regularly.  Also, they aren’t consuming refined sugars or flours, fatty meats, genetically modified foods, or the typical junk foods we like to binge on every now and then.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Not to mention, they spend almost all of their time in nature, perfecting their breathing techniques and meditating, practices that have been shown to boost mental, physical and emotional wellbeing.  And finally, they get proper sleep and spend time in the sun, something that we all typically refer to as “vacation” nowadays.</span>\n\nTreating our bodies right is the first step to living a long, happy and healthy life.  We just have to be disciplined and determined.  How long do you want to live?\n\n\n	\N	<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Have you ever wondered what it might be