1424	553d85f0-83bb-47b8-aa92-c51ed9d415b1	You Won't Beleive What Apple Cider Vinegar Does To Your Face	apple-cider	\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">You don’t really hear much about the benefits that **[apple cider vinegar](http://authoritynutrition.com/6-proven-health-benefits-of-apple-cider-vinegar/)** provides for your skin.  It costs less than practically every other face product on the market, yet still offers the same positive effects.  It combats acne and reduces the appearance of age spots.</span>\n\n**[Alpha hydroxy acids](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alpha_hydroxy_acid)**are one of the active molecules found in apple cider vinegar, which help to remove dead skin cells.  These acids can be found in the expensive face products, but the apple cider vinegar holds much more of its content.\n\nIf you’re looking to use it for age spots, just grab a cotton ball and apply a small amount of diluted apple cider vinegar to it.  Then dab the spots with the cotton ball, leaving the substance on your face for about 20-30 minutes before rinsing it off.\n\nThe acidic nature of apple cider vinegar provides natural antibacterial and antifungal properties, helping heal and prevent acne and skin infections.  It unclogs the pores, helping your skin to breathe, which in turn keeps pimples from forming.  Furthermore, it balances the pH balance of your skin, giving it a nice balance between oily and dry.\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Apple cider vinegar is a strong solution and it can damage your skin, so it’s important to dilute it before applying it to your person.  </span>**You can always make your own face wash using this method:**\n\n**Ingredients – **<span style="font-weight: 400;">1 tablespoon of apple cider vinegar + 3 tablespoons of water</span>\n\n**How to prepare – **<span style="font-weight: 400;">Using a small bowl, mix one tablespoon of apple cider vinegar with 3 tablespoons of water.  After you wet your face with water, rub the combination all over your skin using a cotton ball.  Your best option is organic apple cider vinegar, as this type includes the natural enzymes, bacteria and minerals that provide the positive effects.</span>\n\n(h/t [**My Life Style**](http://www.myilifestyle.com/what-happens-to-your-face-after-washing-it-with-apple-cider-vinegar-this-will-surprise-you/))\n\n\n	\N	<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">You don’t really hear much about the benefits that <strong><a href="http://authoritynutrition.com/6-proven-health-benefits-of-apple-cider-vinegar/">apple cider vinegar</a></strong> provides for your skin.  It costs less than practically every other face product on the market, yet still offers the same positive effects.  It combats acne and reduces the appearance of age spots.</span></p>\n\n<p><strong><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alpha_hydroxy_acid">Alpha hydroxy acids</a></strong>are one of the active molecules found in apple cider vinegar, which help to remove dead skin cells.  These acids can be found in the expensive face products, but the apple cider vinegar holds much more of its content.</p>\n\n<p>If you’re looking to use it for age spots, just grab a cotton ball and apply a small amount of diluted apple cider vinegar to it.  Then dab the spots with the cotton ball, leaving the substance on your face for about 20-30 minutes before rinsing it off.</p>\n\n<p>The acidic nature of apple cider vinegar provides natural antibacterial and antifungal properties, helping heal and prevent acne and skin infections.  It unclogs the pores, helping your skin to breathe, which in turn keeps pimples from forming.  Furthermore, it balances the pH balance of your skin, giving it a nice balance between oily and dry.</p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Apple cider vinegar is a strong solution and it can damage your skin, so it’s important to dilute it before applying it to your person.  </span><strong>You can always make your own face wash using this method:</strong></p>\n\n<p><em>*Ingredients – *</em><span style="font-weight: 400;">1 tablespoon of apple cider vinegar + 3 tablespoons of water</span></p>\n\n<p><em>*How to prepare – *</em><span style="font-weight: 400;">Using a small bowl, mix one tablespoon of apple cider vinegar with 3 tablespoons of water.  After you wet your face with water, rub the combination all over your skin using a cotton ball.  Your best option is organic apple cider vinegar, as this type includes the natural enzymes, bacteria and minerals that provide the positive effects.</span></p>\n\n<p>(h/t <a href="http://www.myilifestyle.com/what-happens-to-your-face-after-washing-it-with-apple-cider-vinegar-this-will-surprise-you/"><strong>My Life Style</strong></a>)</p>	http://cdn.heartcenteredrebalancing.com/2016/06/feature_image_temhfjjfhplate.jpg	f	f	published	en_US	public	\N	\N	1	2016-06-13 05:49:02+00	1	2016-06-13 05:50:25+00	1	2016-06-13 05:49:02+00	1
1425	1f9b7eeb-05d9-4d52-af30-6d63107d96d5	Learn to Grow Lemons From Seed and Have Lemons for Life	learn-to-grow-lemons-from-seed-and-have-lemons-for-life	\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">You always hear the phrase ‘when life gives you lemons..’ being said when times are tough.  But it takes on a whole new meaning after you learn how to grow your own lemon tree, because now when life gives you lemons, you simply plant and grow more lemons!</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Growing your own lemon tree is easy and highly rewarding, making it a fun little side project if you’re looking for something to do or simply want a steady supply of lemons.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Lemon trees grow their very hardest when they’re outdoors, year-round, in a hot and sunny climate.  However, they can be grown inside during seasons with cold or not ideal climates.</span>\n\n**To start growing your lemon tree – Procure the following items**\n\n- <span style="font-weight: 400;">An organic lemon since non-organic lemons often contain non-germinating seeds</span>\n- <span style="font-weight: 400;">Fertile potting soil, preferably containing peat, vermiculite, perlite, and natural fertilizers</span>\n- <span style="font-weight: 400;">A planting pot that is six inches wide and six inches deep (will be used for sprouting)</span>\n- <span style="font-weight: 400;">A seedling pot that is about 24 inches wide by 12 inches deep</span>\n- <span style="font-weight: 400;">A sunny, indoor growing location and possibly a grow light</span>\n\n**Use these steps to grow your lemon tree**\n\n1. <span style="font-weight: 400;">Moisten the potting soil so that it is damp, but not soaked, all the way through.</span>\n2. <span style="font-weight: 400;">Fill the smaller pot with soil, all the way up to an inch below the rim.</span>\n3. <span style="font-weight: 400;">Cut open your lemon and remove a seed. Remove all of the pulp from its surface. A good way to do this is to simply suck on it until it is clean.</span>\n4. <span style="font-weight: 400;">Do not delay to plant. The seed must still be moist when it is buried into the soil. Plant the seed about half an inch deep in the middle of the pot.</span>\n5. <span style="font-weight: 400;">Spray the soil that is directly above the seed gently with water from a spray bottle.</span>\n6. <span style="font-weight: 400;">Cover the pot with clear plastic wrap, seal the edges with a good rubber band, and poke small holes in the top with a pencil.</span>\n7. <span style="font-weight: 400;">Place the pot in a warm, sunny location.</span>\n8. <span style="font-weight: 400;">Spray on more water occasionally, not allowing the soil to dry out. Do not cause water to puddle though. Just keep the soil somewhat moist.</span>\n9. <span style="font-weight: 400;">After about two weeks, when the sproutling emerges, take the plastic covering off. If you need additional light for your lemon plant, you can use a grow light to supplement the sun’s light.</span>\n10. <span style="font-weight: 400;">Take care of the young plant by keeping the soil damp, by making sure it gets at least eight full hours of light per day, and by giving it moderate doses of organic fertilizer.</span>\n11. <span style="font-weight: 400;">Watch over your plant to ensure it is not attacked by bugs or diseases. Prune off brown, dead leaves when necessary. Use pesticides if you must. Protect your new lemon tree!</span>\n12. <span style="font-weight: 400;">When the plant outgrows its small pot, put it in the larger pot. You will go through much the same procedure when you re-plant it as when you first planted. Younger plants need more water than older plants, but they all do need adequate water. Don’t starve your poor plant after all that work of growing it!</span>\n\n<iframe allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" height="658" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/57XoFG0QuMI?feature=oembed" width="1170"></iframe>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Not only is it cheaper to grow your own lemons, but you gain real experience growing plant life, making it valuable as well as educational.  Not to mention, you pretty much have fresh lemons whenever you want them and the lemon tree is a stylish piece of home decor.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">So, take on a new summer project and see if you can grow your own lemon tree.  And be sure to share this fun idea with someone who loves fresh lemons and growing fruit!</span>\n\nh/t [**EcoSnippet**](http://www.ecosnippets.com/gardening/grow-lemons-from-seed/)\n\n\n	\N	<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">You always hear the phrase ‘when life gives you lemons..’ being said when times are tough.  But it takes on a whole new meaning after you learn how to grow your own lemon tree, because now when life gives you lemons, you simply plant and grow more lemons!</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Growing your own lemon tree is easy and highly rewarding, making it a fun little side project if you’re looking for something to do or simply want a steady supply of lemons.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Lemon trees grow their very hardest when they’re outdoors, year-round, in a hot and sunny climate.  However, they can be grown inside during seasons with cold or not ideal climates.</span></p>\n\n<p><strong>To start growing your lemon tree – Procure the following items</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">An organic lemon since non-organic lemons often contain non-germinating seeds</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Fertile potting soil, preferably containing peat, vermiculite, perlite, and natural fertilizers</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">A planting pot that is six inches wide and six inches deep (will be used for sprouting)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">A seedling pot that is about 24 inches wide by 12 inches deep</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">A sunny, indoor growing location and possibly a grow light</span></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>Use these steps to grow your lemon tree</strong></p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Moisten the potting soil so that it is damp, but not soaked, all the way through.</span>  </li>\n<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Fill the smaller pot with soil, all the way up to an inch below the rim.</span>  </li>\n<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Cut open your lemon and remove a seed. Remove all of the pulp from its surface. A good way to do this is to simply suck on it until it is clean.</span>  </li>\n<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Do not delay to plant. The seed must still be moist when it is buried into the soil. Plant the seed about half an inch deep in the middle of the pot.</span>  </li>\n<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Spray the soil that is directly above the seed gently with water from a spray bottle.</span>  </li>\n<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Cover the pot with clear plastic wrap, seal the edges with a good rubber band, and poke small holes in the top with a pencil.</span>  </li>\n<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Place the pot in a warm, sunny location.</span>  </li>\n<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Spray on more water occasionally, not allowing the soil to dry out. Do not cause water to puddle though. Just keep the soil somewhat moist.</span>  </li>\n<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">After about two weeks, when the sproutling emerges, take the plastic covering off. If you need additional light for your lemon plant, you can use a grow light to supplement the sun’s light.</span>  </li>\n<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Take care of the young plant by keeping the soil damp, by making sure it gets at least eight full hours of light per day, and by giving it moderate doses of organic fertilizer.</span>  </li>\n<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Watch over your plant to ensure it is not attacked by bugs or diseases. Prune off brown, dead leaves when necessary. Use pesticides if you must. Protect your new lemon tree!</span>  </li>\n<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">When the plant outgrows its small pot, put it in the larger pot. You will go through much the same procedure when you re-plant it as when you first planted. Younger plants need more water than older plants, but they all do need adequate water. Don’t starve your poor plant after all that work of growing it!</span></li>\n</ol>\n\n<iframe allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" height="658" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/57XoFG0QuMI?feature=oembed" width="1170"></iframe>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Not only is it cheaper to grow your own lemons, but you gain real experience growing plant life, making it valuable as well as educational.  Not to mention, you pretty much have fresh lemons whenever you want them and the lemon tree is a stylish piece of home decor.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">So, take on a new summer project and see if you can grow your own lemon tree.  And be sure to share this fun idea with someone who loves fresh lemons and growing fruit!</span></p>\n\n<p>h/t <a href="http://www.ecosnippets.com/gardening/grow-lemons-from-seed/"><strong>EcoSnippet</strong></a></p>	http://cdn.heartcenteredrebalancing.com/2016/06/feature_image_templasdfasate.jpg	f	f	published	en_US	public	\N	\N	1	2016-06-16 03:48:38+00	1	2016-06-16 03:48:38+00	1	2016-06-16 03:48:38+00	1
