1430	311e31f6-c014-4944-9aa8-1b6a89fb8caa	This Is What Happens To Your Body When You Stop Eating Sugar	this-is-what-happens-to-your-body-when-you-stop-eating-sugar	\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Sugar has been a pretty hot topic in popular culture as the United States continues to be one of the most overweight and unhealthy countries in the world.  The **[National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases](http://www.niddk.nih.gov/Pages/default.aspx)** reports that more than two in three adults are considered to be overweight or obese, more than one in three adults are considered to be obese, and about one out of every twenty adults are considered to have extreme obesity.</span>\n\nI hope everyone recognizes this as a problem.  **[Two-thirds of our population is at risk for major health problems](http://www.niddk.nih.gov/health-information/health-statistics/Pages/overweight-obesity-statistics.aspx)**, and we’ve all but identified the major culprits.  The main one is sugar.  Consumption of high-sugar content drinks and beverages is a major contributor to the obesity epidemic.  Your average 20-ounce soda has anywhere from **[15 to 18 teaspoons of sugar in it, and around 240 calories](http://www.hsph.harvard.edu/nutritionsource/sugary-drinks-fact-sheet/)**.  It’s basically liquid candy, except you don’t feel as “full” after drinking it.\n\n**Here are four things that happen to your body when you quit sugar:**\n\n**You gain energy – **<span style="font-weight: 400;">The more sugar you consume, the more inhibited your body’s ability to sustain energy at maximum levels becomes.  When this happens, our blood sugar levels become imbalanced.  Compared to a person who consumes sugar regularly, those who do not consume sugar benefit from improved ability to generate and store energy.  These people tend to eat foods that are high in energy content, but low in sugar content.</span>\n\n**Your weight stabilizes – **<span style="font-weight: 400;">If you’re consuming sugar on a regular basis, you’re going to gain weight and there’s no getting around it.  Especially in grown adults, sugar has been seen as directly correlated with extreme weight gain and increased risk of chronic illness.  You often hear of “beer bellies” because, well, they’re actually a thing.  Beer contains a high amount of sugar, which causes fat to build up around our tummy area.  When we quit sugar, our bodies equalize and find a natural balance.</span>\n\n**You reduce your risk for chronic illness – **<span style="font-weight: 400;">**[Diabetes is one of the most common chronic illnesses](http://www.diabetes.org/)** that is associated with obesity and unhealthy weight.  It’s main contributor is, unsurprisingly, sugar.  What’s even worse is that Diabetes can serve as a form of gateway illness, opening up the floodgates for other chronic illnesses that are at their strongest when the immune system is weak.  Quitting sugar entirely gives one the opportunity to live a chronic-illness-free life.</span>\n\n**You’ll start disliking sugar – **<span style="font-weight: 400;">Sugar is just like any other chemical in that when you abuse it, your body becomes addicted to it.  Alcohol, tobacco, methamphetamines, uppers, downers, you name it, if you consume them in large quantities and often, your body will crave it.  While just the opposite is true as well: if you stop consuming something altogether, your craving for that substance disappears.  So, do yourself a favor and quit sugar today, or at least limit your intake.</span>\n\nh/t[** Top Health News**](http://tophealthnews.net/see-what-happens-to-your-body-when-you-quit-sugar/)\n\n\n	\N	<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Sugar has been a pretty hot topic in popular culture as the United States continues to be one of the most overweight and unhealthy countries in the world.  The <strong><a href="http://www.niddk.nih.gov/Pages/default.aspx">National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases</a></strong