1459	9317f384-2fac-4f50-8b7c-ea8bc0dc7ba3	What You Never Knew About Giraffes Is Going to Make You Cry	what-you-never-knew-about-giraffes-is-going-to-make-you-cry	\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Giraffes are one of the most widely recognizable animals on the planet due to their long necks and somewhat goofy looking, but adorable faces.  Their iconic status in Africa is well known, but **[new research](http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/aje.12220/epdf)** is showing that they might be in trouble.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">All over the continent, giraffes are disappearing in great numbers.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Since the year 1998, there has been a massive 43 percent decrease in population, leaving about 80,000 of the creatures to graze across 21 African nations, highlights the study.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">What’s actually causing such a dramatic decline in their numbers can be attributed to a number of things, including habitat loss, human-wildlife conflicts, and poaching and slashing.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">It is worse in different regions of the continent, like in the Democratic Republic of Congo, where giraffes are close to being “locally” extinct with only 30 or 40 giraffes alive in the country, says Stephanie Fennessy, program director with the **[Giraffe Conservation Foundation](http://www.giraffeconservation.org/)**(GCF).</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">“The perception is that giraffe numbers are huge. And that they are everywhere. And there’s no need to protect them,” Fennessy told The Dodo.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">This perception is slowly starting to become realized as false, and now time is no longer on their side.  One sort of ‘silver lining’ to these animals being researched, however, is that scientists are continuing to learn more about the giraffe’s capacity for emotion, and are weeding out old myths in the process.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Zoe Muller, founder of the </span>**[Rothschild’s Giraffe Project](http://www.girafferesearch.com/)**<span style="font-weight: 400;">, says, “</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Ask any safari guide in Africa about their behavior and they will delight in telling you how female giraffe are bad mothers, apparently abandoning their young hours after giving birth and leaving them alone and vulnerable in the African bush.” </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">A notion that Muller has found to be untrue.  One giraffe that she followed during her research gave birth to a calf in the spring of 2010.  At around one month of age and suffering from a deformed leg, the calf struggled to walk and rarely moved because of it.  But the mother giraffe never left its side.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">“[S]he could always be found next to her calf, standing with it and being vigilant to the surrounding area,” Muller wrote.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Unfortunately, the baby calf passed away one morning, most likely due to natural causes.  But, shortly after, Muller discovered 17 other female giraffes </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">“all highly vigilant and running around in apparently bizarre patterns.”</span>\n\n<iframe allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" height="658" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/8bI20ZglxOI?feature=oembed" width="1170"></iframe>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">While Muller is reluctant to categorize their behavior as “mourning,” she acknowledges that it is similar to another mammal that is notorious for their grieving of lost loved ones: elephants.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">“It is well documented that elephants show great interest in the carcasses and bones of other dead elephants and herd members, often viewed as evidence of their empathic nature and ability to ‘mourn’ their dead,” she says.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">“…</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">we are only just beginning to understand the complexities of their social systems and family networks. This incident provides us a unique insight into one aspect of giraffe behavior that we are rarely afforded a glance of — that of family ties and effects of the loss of a herd member.”</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">You can watch a video of the incident **[here](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8bI20ZglxOI)**, and below is video of a mother giraffe who took on a pride of lions after they took her calf, showcasing the female giraffe’s willingness to endure danger for the sake of their young.</span>\n\n<iframe allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" height="878" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/VhMU_F3arSA?feature=oembed" width="1170"></iframe>\n\nh/t [**The Dodo**](https://www.thedodo.com/giraffe-mothers-conservation-1170369798.html)\n\n\n	\N	<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Giraffes are one of the most widely recognizable animals on the planet due to their long necks and somewhat goofy looking, but adorable faces.  Their iconic status in Africa is well known, but <strong><a href="http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/aje.12220/epdf">new research</a></strong> is showing that they might be in trouble.  </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">All over the continent, giraffes are disappearing in great numbers.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Since the year 1998, there has been a massive 43 percent decrease in population, leaving about 80,000 of the creatures to graze across 21 African nations, highlights the study.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">What’s actually causing such a dramatic decline in their numbers can be attributed to a number of things, including habitat loss, human-wildlife conflicts, and poaching and slashing.  </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">It is worse in different regions of the continent, like in the Democratic Republic of Congo, where giraffes are close to being “locally” extinct 