1460	292e8b7a-8a15-48e3-b319-f44da90ef1ff	How To Check If the Pavement is Too Hot For Your Dog	how-to-check-if-the-pavement-is-too-hot-for-your-dog	\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Every good dog owner probably has the basics of pup safety down when it comes to surviving the summer heat.  Things like bringing lots of water with you wherever you go, looking for **[signs that they’re overheating](https://www.thedodo.com/how-to-tell-dog-overheating-1224088290.html)**, and never ever leaving them in the car, are common knowledge.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">But even some of the most caring and loving of owners forget that the ground itself can be incredibly hot, sometimes so hot that it can cause quite a bit of suffering for your pup and his or her feet.</span>\n\n![](https://scontent-yyz1-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t1.0-0/p403x403/13331152_1093673134044659_2165758981826158917_n.jpg?oh=f46f4b94423bc94affda1089bfab71ee&oe=582B4825)\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">And you undoubtedly know what it feels like.  Remember as a kid, walking onto the hot pavement of your street or the hot sand of the beach and thinking, “Wow, this really hurts. I’m going to not walk on this anymore.”  It’s the same thing your dog is thinking.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">“Asphalt gets very hot and can burn your pet’s paws, so walk your dog on the grass if possible,” the </span>**[Humane Society of the United States](http://www.humanesociety.org/animals/resources/tips/pets_safe_heat_wave.html)**<span style="font-weight: 400;"> says.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">However, sometimes it can be hard to tell.  So, **[Moon Valley Canine Training ](https://www.facebook.com/pages/Moon-Valley-Canine-Training/185614088146445)**has come up with a quick and easy test to help you determine whether or not your dog is safe walking on a hot surface:</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Place the back of your hand on the pavement and try to hold it there for at least five seconds, if you can’t do this, then the surface is too hot for your pup to walk on safely.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">If the pavement is indeed too hot, wait until the heat has subsided a bit to take them on a walk, or make them stay on grass.  If walking on the hot pavement is something that cannot be avoided, test out **[other protection methods](http://petslady.com/articles/10_tips_protect_your_dogs_paws_hot_pavement_57624)**, like dog booties or special wax designed to coat their paws, protecting them from heat.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">You can learn more about how to keep your dogs safe and happy this summer here.  And don’t forget to share with friends and family who might need a quick reminder of dog safety!</span>\n\nh/t [**The Dodo**](https://www.thedodo.com/how-to-tell-if-the-pavement-is-too-hot-for-your-dogs-feet-1242363093.html)\n\n\n	\N	<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Every good dog owner probably has the basics of pup safety down when it comes to surviving the summer heat.  Things like bringing lots of water with you wherever you go, looking for <strong><a href="https://www.thedodo.com/how-to-tell-dog-overheating-1224088290.html">signs that they’re overheating</a></strong>, and never ever leaving them in the car, are common knowledge.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">But even some of the most caring and loving of owners forget that the ground itself can be incredibly hot, sometimes so hot that it can cause quite a bit of suffering for your pup and his or her feet.</span></p>\n\n<p><img src="https://scontent-yyz1-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t1.0-0/p403x403/13331152_1093673134044659_2165758981826158917_n.jpg?oh=f46f4b94423bc94affda1089bfab71ee&amp;oe=582B4825" alt="" /></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">And you undoubtedly know what it feels like.  Remember as a kid, walking onto the hot pavement of your street or the hot sand of the beach and thinking, “Wow, this really hurts. I’m going to not walk on this a