1462	055d4d9d-5ff4-4e15-9c02-64fe4be40799	5 Side Effects of Meditation to Watch Out For	5-side-effects-of-meditation-to-watch-out-for	\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Meditation is often viewed by those who have never tried it as a bunch of mumbo-jumbo spiritual non-sense, but that notion could not be further from the truth.  Meditation goes much deeper than simple relaxation, it actually provides a number of health benefits for the body and the mind.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">And the best part is that it’s entirely free and anyone can learn how to do it.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Here are five positive things one can gain by practicing meditation regularly:</span>\n\n**Lasting control over your emotions**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Meditation brings us down to a calmed state while we’re practicing it, and it’s been seen that this calmed state actually stays with us after we’ve finished meditating.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">One study **[scanned the brains of people before and after an 8-week meditation course](http://dx.doi.org/10.3389/fnhum.2012.00292)**, finding reduced activation of the amygdala (the center of emotion in the brain) across all pictures, suggesting meditation benefits exist far after the act of meditation is over.</span>\n\n**Increased compassion and virtue**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">To test the compassion of meditators, a study used actors to see which participants would come to the aid of a person appearing to be in pain.  One actor would come into the staged waiting room on crutches, grimacing in pain, while two other actors sat idly by ignoring the person in pain, so as to give off social cues that no one should intervene.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Participants who had been meditating **[were found to be 50 percent more likely](http://dx.doi.org/10.1177/0956797613485603)** to help the person in pain.</span>\n\n**It changes the brain structure, in a good way**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Eight weeks is all it takes for meditation to manipulate the brain’s structure. One study **[looked at the images of 16 people’s brains](http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.pscychresns.2010.08.006)**before and after they participated in a meditation program.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">When compared to the control group, subjects experienced an increase in grey-matter density in the area of the brain responsible for learning and memory.</span>\n\n**It promotes creativity**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">If you’ve been struggling to solve a problem for quite sometime and have run out of answers, try meditating on it.  One study had participants **[come up with as many uses for a brick](http://dx.doi.org/10.3389/fpsyg.2012.00116)**as they could, a traditional creativity task.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Participants who practiced an ‘open monitoring’ meditation technique were able to think up the most uses for the brick.  This type of meditation technique uses focus on one’s breathing to open up the mind.</span>\n\n**Greater ability to concentrate**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">When you look at the fundamentals of meditation, concentration is at the core of it: the ability to **[control your brain’s attention](http://www.spring.org.uk/2009/03/the-attentional-spotlight.php)**.  Numerous studies have found that meditation provides a number of benefits for concentration and attention.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">One study had 17 people who had never meditated in their lives take an 8-week course **[on mindfulness-based stress reduction meditation](http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17672382)**to monitor its effects.  When compared to the control group, these 17 people exhibited heightened levels of concentration and greater ability to focus their attention.</span>\n\n\n	\N	<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Meditation is often viewed by those who have never tried it as a bunch of mumbo-jumbo spiritual non-sense, but that notion could not be further from the truth.  Meditation goes much deeper than simple relaxation, it actually provides a number of health benefits for the body and the mind.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">And the best part is that it’s entirely free and anyone can learn how to do it.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Here are five positive things one can gain by practicing meditation regularly:</span></p>\n\n<p><strong>Lasting control over your emotions</strong></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Meditation brings us down to a calmed state while we’re practicing it, and it’s been seen that this calmed state actually stays with us after we’ve finished meditating.  </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">One study <strong><a href="http://dx.doi.org/10.3389/fnhum.2012.00292">scanned the brains of people before and after an 8-week meditation course</a></strong>, finding reduced activation of the amygdala (the center of emotion in the brain) across all pictures, suggesting meditation benefits exist far after the act of meditation is over.</span></p>\n\n<p><strong>Increased compassion and virtue</strong></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">To test the compassion of meditators, a study used actors to see which participants would come to the aid of a person appearing to be in pain.  One actor would come into the staged waiting room on crutches, grimacing in pain, while two other actors sat idly by ignoring the person in pain, so as to give off social cues that no one should intervene.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Participants who had been meditating <strong><a href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1177/0956797613485603">were found to be 50 percent more likely</a></strong> to help the person in pain.</span></p>\n\n<p><strong>It changes the brain structure, in a good way</strong></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Eight weeks is all it takes for meditation to manipulate th