1510	921822db-92f3-4146-aec1-cb7c9bed1695	5 Rules of Facebook Etiquette That Everyone Should Respect	5-rules-of-facebook-etiquette-that-everyone-should-respect	<span style="font-weight: 400;">Facebook is a social landscape that many of us have been navigating since we were kids. Over the years, as in any type of social setting, unspoken ‘rules’ have been set in place by the people that operate within that setting. </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">You know what I’m talking about. When you’re scrolling your newsfeed and a dramatic, paragraph-length post pops up from one of your friends who is visibly upset and angry about something? How many times have you rolled your eyes because you thought to yourself, “Facebook really is not the place you should be bashing your ex-girlfriend.”</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Here are five rules of Facebook etiquette that we should all get on board with to make Facebook a better place for everyone:</span>\n\n<b>Vaguebooking</b>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">When I was in my angsty teen years, I was all about ‘vaguebooking.’ Vaguebooking is basically a clickbait-styled post that is purposely vague so as to draw attention to it, or to passive-aggressively send a message to a person they’re angry with.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">When I did it, I usually posted song lyrics that I knew no one would recognize, but secretly hoped they would. Other times, it shows up as stuff like, “I can’t believe he would do that to me, what a jerk.” No one really has any idea what you’re talking about.</span>\n\n<b>Announcements</b>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Announcements on Facebook are not inherently bad. In fact, I would argue that social media was created to give us the ability to reach a wide audience with our messages. </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">The etiquette part of this depends entirely on the importance of the announcement. Throwing out details to a party this weekend is fine. But, when it’s something big and important, a phone call to the people who really matter in your life is much more tasteful. </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">The last thing you want is your siblings or parents finding out about your engagement on Facebook.</span>\n\n<b>Using Facebook to promote other social media</b>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">While some people like to use </span><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">every</span></i><span style="font-weight: 400;"> form of social media available today, many Facebookers could care less about what’s happening on Twitter or Tumblr. </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">If we were really interested in what you’re doing on these other platforms, we’d be using that other platform. It’s best to keep Facebook undiluted.</span>\n\n<b>Discussing matters that are not yours to discuss</b>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">When your friends and family are going through a tough time, you always want to help them out. But if you think that you’re helping them by spreading the word about it, you could be very wrong. </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Many people don’t want their personal issues and problems broadcast to the world. Ask them before you start making posts requesting the sympathies of others.</span>\n\n<b>Mundane posts about everything in your life</b>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">“Ate a pork chop for dinner and had nice applesauce too,” reads Kip Drordy’s status update in an episode of <em>South Park</em>. </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Do you ever use Facebook to let everyone know the small details of your everyday life? Because if you do, you should stop.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Facebook is a great tool for sharing information and communicating with each other, but no one really cares if you went to the gym or what outfit you picked for the day.</span>\n\nh/t [SOL](http://www.simpleorganiclife.org/rules-of-fbook-1842555900.html?c=ss)	\N	<p><span style="fo