1476	969c81e0-6152-49e5-8a06-efa415fd5080	This Colorado City Created Affordable Housing Almost Overnight	this-colorado-city-created-affordable-housing-almost-overnight	\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Housing is easily one of the most expensive parts of anyone’s budget, with most experts suggesting that you only spend about a third of your monthly income on housing, max.  But if you’re like the millions of people around the country who are currently spending at least half or more of their income on housing, you know life can be tough.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">**[Durango, Colorado](https://www.planning.org/events/nationalconferenceactivity/9001901/)**, is one city that was seeking a way to create affordable housing, and instead of building new infrastructure, decided to tweak some of their rules and policies.  Much of how they did this surrounds ‘Accessory Dwelling Units,’ which are basically the finished basements, above-garage studios, rebuilt carriage houses, and other similar type buildings that rest on lots typically zoned for single-family homes.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">City officials realized that Durango already had a plethora of ADUs in and around the city, but no one could live in them because of the restrictions put in place that tightly regulate who can live in them.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Starting in 2009, Durango worked on overhauling its Land Use and Development Code.  Under their revised code, standards were put in place to guide the development of new ADUs, including a limit on how many occupants they could have (five unrelated persons), rules on how small the living space could be (550 sq. ft.), rules on owner-occupied home requirements (meaning landlords cannot be absent while renting out both their home and ADU), and bans on short-term vacation rentals like through AirBnB.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Existing ADUs were the only real problem with the new code, because no one knew what to do with them.  Most of them were considered illegal, so to bypass this with as little pain as possible, a type of “ADU amnesty” was put in place as officials asked owners of current ADUs with residents to come forward.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Having an established ADU that was completely under the radar, meaning it wasn’t official in any way, landed people fines ranging from $2000 to $9000, but they got to keep their ADUs, they were just logged into the city’s inventory database.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">This ADU amnesty program was largely successful, as this sort of informal and underground economy was regularized with the coming forward of more and more people who were operating unofficial ADUs.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Some members of the Durango community opposed this new code, suggesting that it would turn much of the neighborhoods and residential areas into ‘slums,’ instead of viewing the work as progress toward affordable housing.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Durango’s story comes at a perfect time, as **[more and more communities](http://www.seattletimes.com/opinion/mother-in-law-units-are-key-to-housing-affordability/) from [around the country](http://www.bostonglobe.com/opinion/2016/04/30/how-grandma-can-help-housing-crunch/BBul6fbzcinQ4iEPtsmvVJ/story.html?)** struggle to address similar housing problems.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">What do you think about Durango’s push to create affordable housing?  Are they doing it the right way?</span>\n\nh/t [**City Lab**](http://www.citylab.com/design/2016/05/how-one-colorado-city-instantly-created-affordable-housing/483027/)\n\n\n	\N	<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Housing is easily one of the most expensive parts of anyone’s budget, with most experts suggesting that you only spend about a third of your monthly income on housing, max.  But if you’re like the millions of people around the country who are currently spending at least half or more of their income on housing, you know life can be tough.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;"><strong><a href="https://www.planning.org/events/nationalconferenceactivity/9001901/">Durango, Colorado</a></strong>, is one city that was seeking a way to create affordable housing, and instead of building new infrastructure, decided to tweak some of their rules and policies.  Much of how they did this surrounds ‘Accessory Dwelling Units,’ which are basically the finished basements, above-garage studios, rebuilt carriage houses, and other similar type buildings that rest on lots typically zoned for single-family homes.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">City officials realized that Durango already had a plethora of ADUs in and around the city, but no one could live in them because of the restrictions put in place that tightly regulate who can live in them.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Starting in 2009, Durango worked on overhauling its Land Use and Development Code.  Under their revised code, standards were put in place to guide the development of new ADUs, including a limit on how many occupants they could have (five unrelated persons), rules on how small the living space could be (550 sq. ft.), rules on owner-occupied home requirements (meaning landlords cannot be absent while renting out both their home and ADU), and bans on short-term vacation rentals like through AirBnB.  </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Existing ADUs were the only real problem with the new code, because no one knew what to do with them.  Most of them were considered illegal, so to bypass this with as little pain as possible, a type of “ADU amnesty” was put in place as officials asked owners of current ADUs with residents to come forward.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Having an established ADU that was completely under the radar, meaning it wasn’t official in any way, landed people fines ranging from $2000 to $9000, but they got to keep their ADUs, they were just logged into the city’s inventory database.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">This ADU amnesty program was largely successful, as this sort of informal and underground economy was regularized with the coming forward of more and more people who were operating unofficial ADUs.  </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Some members of the Durango community opposed this new code, suggesting that it would turn much of the neighborhoods and residential areas into ‘slums,’ instead of viewing the work as progress toward affordable housing.  </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Durango’s story comes at a perfect time, as <strong><a href="http://www.seattletimes.com/opinion/mother-in-law-units-are-key-to-housing-affordability/">more and more communities</a> from <a href="http://www.bostonglobe.com/opinion/2016/04/30/how-grandma-can-help-housing-crunch/BBul6fbzcinQ4iEPtsmvVJ/story.html?">around the country</a></strong> struggle to address similar housing problems.  </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">What do you think about Durango’s push to create affordable housing?  Are they doing it the right way?</span></p>\n\n<p>h/t <a href="http://www.citylab.com/design/2016/05/how-one-colorado-city-instantly-created-affordable-housing/483027/"><strong>City Lab</strong></a></p>	http://cdn.heartcenteredrebalancing.com/2016/07/feature_imageasdfasdff_template.jpg	f	f	published	en_US	public	\N	\N	1	2016-07-22 04:28:53+00	1	2016-07-22 04:28:53+00	1	2016-07-22 04:28:53+00	1
1477	91dcccc2-190c-4b61-9203-5cc776880640	Your Zodiac Sign Says A Lot About How You Express Anger	your-zodiac-sign-says-a-lot-about-how-you-express-anger	\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Anger is one of those emotions that comes out in everyone differently. Some of us have short fuses that ignite some of the biggest bombs ever seen; others let their angry thoughts bounce around inside of them, reluctant to express them. </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Your Zodiac sign has a lot to do with how you handle your anger. And knowing how to handle your anger is the first step in building healthier, more positive thought patterns.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Here is how each Zodiac sign expresses anger:</span>\n\n**Aries**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">As a fire sign, Aries are known for blowing up and fast. They’re not known for starting arguments or conflict, but they’re incredibly good at ending them. If they aren’t ready to do something, or get forced into something, you will likely see the fire within them. </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">But, just as they’re quick to ignite, they’re quick to forgive and forget.</span>\n\n**Taurus**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">It takes a lot to anger the Taurus, but, should you succeed, good luck trying to make it out alive. They don’t like to waste their energy on angry thoughts, but if you betray them, are disloyal or treat them as inferior, they’re ready to rumble. </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Give them the time and space they need to calm down as they can stay angry for long periods of time.</span>\n\n**Gemini**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">It’s anyone’s guess as to how the Twins will express their anger. They like to cut deep wounds with a calm, centered demeanor, and they absolutely love to talk. So, if you piss them off, you will undoubtedly get an earful. Just don’t tell them what to do and they’ll likely forgive you.</span>\n\n**Cancer**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Underneath the Cancer’s hard and protective shell lies a loyal, understanding and sweet being whose only wish is for people to return their affection. This is what usually upsets the Cancer; feeling unloved or unappreciated. You can always tell when a Cancer is angry because they’ll usually sulk around passive-aggressively. </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Don’t ignore their pleas, it will only hurt them more.</span>\n\n**Leo**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">An angry Leo has no trouble telling you exactly how they feel. Ranting, raving, kicking, screaming.. The leo is very capable of making a grand spectacle. And, they’re quick to say things that really hurt, so if they do, just know that it’s one of the only ways they know how to release their anger: venting. </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">They’re not likely to hold a grudge, however, and will probably move past most conflicts fairly fast.</span>\n\n**Virgo**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Known for being both patient and loving, the Virgo has a great capacity for abuse before being set off in an angry way. Because they like to avoid confrontation, Virgos will often become incredibly passive aggressive. </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">They’re not going to hold a grudge, but they’re not going to forget about what you did, either.</span>\n\n**Libra**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">As a peacekeeper, the Libra’s scales fit perfectly here. Balance is valued in everything, especially relationships. This means that confrontation is often avoided, and emotions get bottled up. Even when they’re at the peak of their frustration, Libras do their best to wear a happy face as they hold back their rage. </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">If the hurt is great enough, they are definitely capable of holding a grudge.</span>\n\n**Scorpio**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Similar to other signs, the Scorpio doesn’t let out anger as it comes to them. You can always tell if a Scorpio is angry by looking into their eyes. Their eyes will say more than anything. They’re usually venting in their minds, planning their next move. </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">If they suddenly get really quiet and you see angry eyes come out, give them some space. And don’t try to force them into anything before they’re ready.</span>\n\n**Sagittarius**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Surefire ways to piss off a Sagittarius include dishonesty, disloyalty, being cruel and spewing hate speech. While they tend to be a patient sign, and they don’t angry very often, when they do get angry they’re not interested in playing nice, </span>*<span style="font-weight: 400;">at all</span>*<span style="font-weight: 400;">. </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">You’ll know they’re starting to get angry when the heavy sarcasm starts pouring out.</span>\n\n**Capricorn**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">As an Earth sign, Capricorns aren’t too pent up with anger. They like to keep things easy-going, but also have a threshold you can reach. You’re most likely to piss them off by accidentally messing up the ‘zen’ of their space. </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Capricorns get angry for seemingly random reasons, and they don’t like to express it. They enjoy sulking before they’re ready to throw a tantrum.</span>\n\n**Aquarius**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Arguing is the last thing the Aquarius wants to do, so that’s what they tend to avoid, choosing to completely ignore people instead. If they can’t seem to get away from whatever it is that’s upsetting them, they’re likely to blow up just because of how frustrated they are. </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Depending on who they’re arguing with, they may or may not want to continue the relationship.</span>\n\n**Pisces**\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">The Pisces is somewhat volatile, meaning you never know what’s going to light their fuse. If they’re having a bad day alrea