1493	bf47944a-33d8-41ac-bb35-a32f9bccc0b2	Man Takes His Dying Dog On One Last Adventure	man-takes-his-dying-dog-on-one-last-adventure	\nAll Photos Courtesy of [**Kugler and Bella**](https://www.facebook.com/robert.kugler1).\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">“Man’s best friend” has been the phrase used to describe our canine companions for as long as we can remember, and with good reason.  Dogs make some of the best pets and most owners come to see them as their children or members of the family.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Thus, one of the saddest parts of dog ownership is knowing that you will likely outlive your best friend, a possibility that turned into reality for Robert Kugler.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Kugler’s best friend was a chocolate labrador named Bella, and she was diagnosed with bone cancer in her leg. After her leg was amputated, Kugler hoped that would be the end of it, but the cancer had actually spread to Bella’s lungs and was now terminal.</span>\n\n![ ](http://i2.cdn.turner.com/cnnnext/dam/assets/160713132208-bella-cleveland-exlarge-169.jpg)\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">“This is one of the biggest connections I’ve ever had to another living being. I don’t care that it’s a dog,” said Kugler.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Kugler has been with his pup since adopting her about nine years ago, so finding out that she might not around for much longer was devastating.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">“I just didn’t want her to be gone one day when I came home,” he said.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">So, Kugler decided that he and Bella needed to take one last adventure together, their biggest one yet.  Starting out at the Marine Corps. Ball in Chicago (because Kugler is a Marine veteran), Bella and Kugler travelled to random locations around the region.  </span>\n\n![ ](http://i2.cdn.turner.com/cnnnext/dam/assets/160713132656-belle-niagara-falls-exlarge-169.jpg)\n\n![ ](http://i2.cdn.turner.com/cnnnext/dam/assets/160713133115-bella-fenway-park-exlarge-169.jpg)\n\n![ ](http://i2.cdn.turner.com/cnnnext/dam/assets/160713133331-bella-lincoln-memorial-exlarge-169.jpg)\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">From the Niagra Falls to Fenway Park to the Lincoln Memorial, Kugler and Bella camped out of the car or couchsurfed with friends as they made their way to each new destination.  </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">“I want to inspire people to get outside and live,” Kugler said. “Love each other for who we are and make friends.”</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">While Bella has survived for longer than doctors had anticipated, Kugler recognizes that her time is limited.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">“Some days I’m completely prepared. I pictured her just swimming out to sea,”</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">“But there’s other days when I’m like, oh my God, I can’t bear the thought of it.”</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">“We take on these animals, which means we’re gonna take on their life and their passing,” Kugler said. “To be there with them when they pass is the greatest gift you can give anybody.”</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">After Bella has passed, Kugler says he’ll likely try to spend more time volunteering with organizations like [Team Rubicon](http://www.teamrubiconusa.org/) and [Team Red, White & Blue](https://www.teamrwb.org/), both of which focus on helping veterans.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">In the meantime, Kugler hopes that everyone can be inspired by Bella’s story to “Wag more [and] bark less.”</span>\n\n*You can keep following Kugler and Bella on social media: *\n\n*[Twitter](https://twitter.com/robkugler) | [Facebook](https://www.facebook.com/robert.kugler1) | [Instragram](https://www.instagram.com/robkugler/)*\n\n\n	\N	<p>All Photos Courtesy of <a href="https://www.facebook.com/robert.kugler1"><strong>Kugler and Bella</strong></a>.</p>\n\n<p><span style="f