1499	e18289d0-cd57-4926-a135-8bee94897108	Science Says: This Is How You Should Be Boiling Your Eggs	science-says-this-is-how-you-should-be-boiling-your-eggs	\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">If you’ve ever tried to boil an egg, you know that it’s not the easiest thing in the world. It probably </span>*<span style="font-weight: 400;">feels</span>*<span style="font-weight: 400;"> like it should be the easiest thing in the world, because c’mon, you’re boiling an egg, but it’s often quite difficult to perfect this practice. Do it wrong, and you’re left with an egg no one wants to eat.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Why is it so difficult? Well, eggs actually consist of two parts: the yolk and the white. And each of them have different compositional makeups, which means they also have unique cooking temperatures.</span>\n\n**[According to J. Kenji](http://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/the-food-lab-j-kenji-lopez-alt/1121137395) [López-Alt](http://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/the-food-lab-j-kenji-lopez-alt/1121137395),**<span style="font-weight: 400;"> Egg whites cook best at </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">180°F (82°C). This temperature allows for a sturdy, yet tender egg white. </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">The ideal temperature for the yolk? About 10 degrees hotter than the egg white. But, if you cook the yolk above </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">170°F (77°C), it starts to dry out and crumble.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Peeling is another factor when boiling eggs. If you put your eggs in cold water to begin with, the egg will bind to the shell, which makes peeling them almost impossible. And if you drop your eggs into boiling water, there’s a good chance you’ll cook the whites before the yolks. </span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">So, what should you be doing instead? </span>\n\n[**J. Kenji **<span style="font-weight: 400;">**López-Alt**</span>](http://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/the-food-lab-j-kenji-lopez-alt/1121137395)<span style="font-weight: 400;">suggests starting the eggs in boiling water, so the whites have a chance to cook, but do not stick to the shell. Once they’ve cooked a bit, you begin to add ice cubes in order to lower the water’s temperature. Then you finish with a slow, gradual cook of the eggs.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Specifically, the method looks like this: bring your water to a boil, gently place your eggs in the water and let them sit for 30 seconds. Then, add ice to the water to bring the temperature down. Once you’ve added the ice, you’re pretty much done. Let the water come back up to boiling and cook the eggs for at least 11 minutes at around 190</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">°F.</span>\n\n**Et voilà! **<span style="font-weight: 400;">Perfectly boiled eggs.</span>\n\n \n\n\n	\N	<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">If you’ve ever tried to boil an egg, you know that it’s not the easiest thing in the world. It probably </span><em><span style="font-weight: 400;">feels</span></em><span style="font-weight: 400;"> like it should be the easiest thing in the world, because c’mon, you’re boiling an egg, but it’s often quite difficult to perfect this practice. Do it wrong, and you’re left with an egg no one wants to eat.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Why is it so difficult? Well, eggs actually consist of two parts: the yolk and the white. And each of them have different compositional makeups, which means they also have unique cooking temperatures.</span></p>\n\n<p><strong><a href="http://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/the-food-lab-j-kenji-lopez-alt/1121137395">According to J. Kenji</a> <a href="http://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/the-food-lab-j-kenji-lopez-alt/1121137395">López-Alt</a>,</strong><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Egg whites cook best at </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">180°F (82°C). This temperature allows for a sturdy, yet tender egg white. </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">The ideal temperature for the yolk? About