ght? My left-handed friends were always weird. But, that could have all just been in my head. It turns out that left-handed people actually do have some pretty cool traits that are unique to them.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Here are nine facts about left-handed people you probably never knew:</span></p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><strong><em>*Left-handed folks can see better than right-handed folks when under water</em>*</strong>  </li>\n<li><strong>If you’re left-handed, you are at a greater risk for insomnia</strong>  </li>\n<li><strong>Allergies and asthma affect left-handed people worse than right-handed people</strong>  </li>\n<li><strong>About 30 million people in the United States are left-handed</strong>  </li>\n<li><strong>Left-handed people are usually better at architecture</strong>  </li>\n<li><strong>Left-handed folks exhibit a greater command of language</strong>  </li>\n<li><strong>Women 40 years or older are much more likely to have a left-handed child</strong>  </li>\n<li><strong>Left-handed people who graduate college are more likely to be wealthier than right-handed college grads</strong>  </li>\n<li><strong>Out of 7 of the most recent presidents, 4 of them are left-handed</strong></li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>h/t <a href="http://www.higherperspectives.com/left-handed-1546781995.html?page=2"><em>*Higher Perspective *</em></a></p>	http://cdn.heartcenteredrebalancing.com/2016/08/feature_image_temlefthadnplate.jpg	f	f	published	en_US	public	\N	\N	1	2016-08-17 07:54:16+00	1	2016-08-17 07:54:16+00	1	2016-08-17 07:54:16+00	1
1507	5cae41af-781b-42e7-9dac-2f93f7dc79fc	5 Things You Should Do (And 5 Things You Shouldn’t) If You’re Making Friends With an Introvert	5-things-you-should-do-and-5-things-you-shouldnt-if-youre-making-friends-with-an-introvert	<span style="font-weight: 400;">As you continue to get older, making friends continues to get harder. Once we’re out of school and thrusted into the real world, not every day is a social party where you’re surrounded by people you consider your friends. In fact, many people go to great lengths to try and make friends, but the truth is that if the other person isn’t interested, it probably won’t happen.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Which is why it can be so hard to befriend introverts. As quiet, reserved folks, these people often get labeled as strange and unfriendly because, in Western culture, being quiet and reserved carries with it a somewhat negative stigma.</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">But don’t let their behavior or attitude deter you when you know they’d make a good friend if you could get them to open up a little. Introverts make some of the best friends, so here are five things you can do, and five things you should avoid doing, to help your chances:</span>\n\n<b>Things you should try not to do:</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Do your best to never put them “on the spot” when you’re around a large group of people. The attention makes them uncomfortable and embarrassed.</span></li>\n \t<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Don’t try to make small talk. Introverts often despise small talk, preferring instead to discuss matters of actual substance. Plus, small talk puts pressure on them to come up with conversation.</span></li>\n \t<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Don’t act like their shy personality is a certain ‘condition’ or illness. They’re not interested in making friends with people who see them as charity cases.</span></li>\n \t<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">When you’re talking with them, let the conversation flow naturally. If you awkwardly struggle to maintain a conversation, it will make their insides crawl. They hate awkward situations.</span></li>\n \t<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Try not to force them to do anything that is outside of their realm of comfort. They’re simply not going to try something new just because you want them to. They will never trust you again and will likely never want to see you again.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<b>Things you want to do:</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Try to be by yourself when you approach an introvert, as groups of people make introverts feel a tad bit socially overwhelmed.</span></li>\n \t<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Use a soothing, somewhat quiet voice when you speak to them. This puts them at ease and is easier to process than loud, abrasive tones.</span></li>\n \t<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Find a mutual interest or problem and then talk about it together. Introverts like building connections over personal and meaningful conversation.</span></li>\n \t<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Only hang out with them for short periods of time at first. They enjoy having time to work through things, which includes you and everything you’ve said to them. So give them space and time to make up their mind about you.</span></li>\n \t<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Make eye contact only for brief moments. When you maintain eye contact for too long, the brain’s ‘fight-or-flight’ mechanism becomes triggered, making you seem more intimidating than you are.	\N	<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">As you continue to get older, making friends continues to get harder. Once we’re out of school and thrusted into the real world, not every day is a social party where you’re surrounded by people you consider your friends. In fact, many people go to great lengths to try and make friends, but the truth is that if the other person isn’t interested, it probably won’t happen.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Which is why it can be so hard to befriend introverts. As quiet, reserved folks, these people often get labeled as strange and unfriendly because, in Western culture, being quiet and reserved carries with it a somewhat negative stigma.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">But don’t let their behavior or attitude deter you when you know they’d make a good friend if you could get them to open up a little. Introverts make some of the best friends, so here are five things you can do, and five things you should avoid doing, to help your chances:</span></p>\n\n<p><b>Things you should try not to do:</b>  </p>\n\n<ul>  \n     <li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Do your best to never put them “on the spot” when you’re around a large group of people. The attention makes them uncomfortable and embarrassed.</span></li>\n     <li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Don’t try to make small talk. Introverts often despise small talk, preferring instead to discuss matters of actual substance. Plus, small talk puts pressure on them to come up with conversation.</span></li>\n     <li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Don’t act like their shy personality is a certain ‘condition’ or illness. They’re not interested in making friends with people who see them as charity cases.</span></li>\n     <li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">When you’re talking with them, let the conversation flow naturally. If you awkwardly struggle to maintain a conversation, it will make their insides crawl. They hate awkward situations.</span></li>\n     <li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 40