1513	8be1e596-0bc2-4c3d-912b-c14d395f9e9c	5 Great Health Benefits You Gain by Knitting and Crocheting	5-great-health-benefits-you-gain-by-knitting-and-crocheting	As humans, many of the things we do in life are therapeutic in nature. We’re always finding new ways to ease our conscience and put the mind at peace. String-based crafts have been a favorite pastime for humans for ages, but it makes sense because we derive so much happiness from being able to make things using our hands.\n\nWell, as it turns out, knitting, crocheting, lacemaking and many other string-based creative practices can actually improve your health in a variety of different ways.\n\nHere are five health benefits you pick up by practicing your hand at knitting and crocheting!\n\n**Reduced blood pressure and lower heart rate**\n\nFor those who already knit and crochet regularly, you’re fully aware of just how relaxing this craft can be and it’s probably part of the reason you do it. Relaxation is great for the human body. It helps reduce the production of cortisol, the body’s stress hormone, which in turn helps keep the heart and circulatory system healthy. Not to mention, stress hurts the body in a variety of other ways as well.\n\n**It keeps your hand-eye coordination sharp**\n\nHave you ever watched someone knit or crochet something? It looks as though their hands are moving a million miles an hour, repeating movements and techniques rapidly in quick succession.\n\nThese quick, repeated movements help improve the health of your hands. It helps keep your joints flexible and your muscles steady. While it might seem like a bad idea for people with arthritis, it’s actually quite helpful for maintaining mobility of the hands. Of course, it’s always good to take breaks too.\n\n**It sharpens math skills**\n\nOne of the coolest parts of knitting and crocheting is how much math is involved. I know, some of you are thinking the opposite, but don’t fret; it’s easy math and you can do it! Counting, multiplyi